"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662998","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>Information provided by the Public Health England health protection team in the East of England, indicates that in mid-November 2016 there was one confirmed case of pulmonary tuberculosis (TB) diagnosed in a patient at Yarls Wood Immigration Removal Centre. As per guidance from the National Institute of Health and Care Excellence, close contacts were identified, amongst whom four women presented with signs and symptoms which could be caused by TB. They were isolated until a fuller assessment was completed. They were not diagnosed with TB.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-11T11:22:49.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662998/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662998/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662998/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-20","Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many women have been held in isolation in Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre in the last month as a result of the recent outbreak of tuberculosis in that centre.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","58656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662999","Home Office","true","2017-01-09","<p>In delivering the Emergency Services Network (ESN), the mobile network operator EE will deliver up to 291 new mast sites. Government will deliver approximately 230 further sites (known as the “Extended Area Services” (EAS) sites) in the most remote and rural areas of Great Britain.</p><p>For EAS sites, the principal objective is to provide coverage to meet the needs of the emergency services, but the Home Office is working with the Scottish Government, Welsh Government and DCMS to identify any proposed mast locations which could improve mobile coverage in future, with a view to ensuring these are built to a specification which could accommodate multiple operators.</p><p>EE has indicated that it is delivering around 200 new sites in Scotland as part of ESN. In addition there are 104 sites in Scotland that are being considered as part of the Extended Area Services (EAS). Delivery of these sites is subject to planning permission and the acquisition of land.<del class="ministerial"> There are currently no new sites proposed in the constituency of Inverclyde, either by EE or the EAS as part of ESN.</del> <ins class="ministerial">There are currently up to 25 new EE ESN sites proposed in the constituency of Orkney and Shetland, and one EAS site as part of ESN.</ins></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-01-09T16:36:14.133Z","2017-01-16T16:20:23.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662999/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662999/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662999/answer","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662999/answer/previousversion/28902","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-20","Aerials: Orkney and Shetland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many emergency services network masts will be built in Orkney and Shetland constituency; and what steps she is taking to ensure that mobile phone services are provided from all four mobile network operators at all such sites.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","58650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663000","Home Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>In March 2016 we published our Violence against Women and Girls (VAWG) Strategy for 2016-2020, which sets out an ambitious programme of reform, supported by increased funding of £80 million.</p><p>As set out in the Strategy, from April 2017 we will move from supporting individual Independent Domestic Violence Advisers (IDVA) and multi-agency risk assessment conference (MARAC) coordinator posts, to a model of supporting community-led services which encourage new approaches through the £15 million VAWG Service Transformation Fund which was announced on 7 December 2016.</p><p>This will help promote better collaboration and joint leadership, encourage new approaches incorporating early intervention, and establish and embed the best ways to help victims, survivors and their families. We have consulted widely with the voluntary and community sector and statutory stakeholders in the development of both the strategy and the Transformation Fund and we will continue to work with the women’s sector to monitor the level of IDVA and MARAC provision.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","58622","2017-01-10T17:57:21.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663000/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663000/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663000/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-20","Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions she has had with local authorities, other commissioners and the voluntary and community sector on planned changes to funding arrangements for independent domestic violence advisers and multi-agency risk assessment conference coordinators from March 2017.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","58623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663001","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Department for Transport does not hold information about the number of foreign registered vehicles circulating illegally in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) continues to work with police forces to address the issue of foreign registered vehicles which stay in the UK longer than six months in any 12 month period without being registered or licensed here. A pilot, which was a joint initiative between the DVLA, the Central Motorway Police Group and Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs (HMRC), ran between November 2014 and February 2015. The pilot involved six police forces, which used information provided by HMRC about foreign vehicles that had been in the UK for more than six months. As a result of this trial, 703 vehicles were seized, of which 500 were reclaimed following payment of the appropriate fees. The remaining 203 vehicles were not claimed within the allotted time and were destroyed.</p><p> </p><p>Currently, 17 police forces have acquired devolved DVLA powers which enable them to take appropriate action against non-compliant foreign registered vehicles.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-01-09T14:13:00.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663001/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663001/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663001/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Motor Vehicles: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answers of 18 November 2016 to Question 50859 and 19 December 2016 to Question 55636, and with reference to the article entitled DVLA works with police and HM Revenue and Customs to crack down on illegal foreign registered vehicles, published on the gov.uk website on 30 January 2015, what assessment has been made of (a) the number of illegal foreign registered vehicles on the roads in the UK and (b) the effectiveness of the DVLA working with the police and HM Revenue and Customs to tackle the presence of such vehicles.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","58608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663002","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>Meeting the 0.7 per cent target for overseas aid is a manifesto commitment. It is enshrined in law and the Government has been unequivocal that we will continue to honour that promise, including reaffirmation by the Prime Minister on 14 December. Alongside our world-class diplomacy commitments and spending two per cent of our GDP on defence, upholding our manifesto commitments on UK aid is vital to securing Britain’s place in the world, helping those less fortunate than ourselves, and exporting economic prosperity, security and stability in the national interest.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2017-01-09T17:27:31.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663002/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663002/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663002/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what her policy is on the Government's long-term commitment to spending 0.7 per cent of gross national income on overseas development assistance.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","58508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663003","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>DFID is working across the international system to ensure that developing country data and systems for reporting against the Sustainable Development Goal (SDG) indicators are appropriately disaggregated, as laid out within Agenda 2030. This includes for older people.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-09T17:17:36.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663003/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663003/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663003/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Developing Countries: Sustainable Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether older people will be included within the indicators used to measure government performance against the Sustainable Development Goals.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","58523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663004","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>DFID has published 2016/17 budgets by department. The allocations are continually reviewed throughout the year and may increase to respond to changing needs. For example, support for Yemen will increase from £90 million in 2015/16 to £112 million in 2016/17 in light of the humanitarian crisis. Final spending figures for all departments will be confirmed in the Department’s Annual Report and Accounts for 2016.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-09T16:52:00.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663004/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663004/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663004/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","South Sudan and Yemen: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, for what reasons the Government reduced the bilateral aid budget to (a) South Sudan and (b) Yemen in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","58524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663005","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>The UK remains committed to supporting poverty reduction in Rwanda, Kenya and Ghana. Kenya and Ghana are now lower-middle income countries and as such are starting to transition from aid.</p><p>Our assistance in all three countries strengthens health and education and supports inclusive economic growth and job creation, which are essential to sustainably reduce poverty and allow a managed transition from aid. Our bilateral assistance is complemented by funding through DFID’s centrally-managed programmes and support through multilaterals and other Government Departments.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-09T17:14:55.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663005/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663005/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663005/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Africa: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to ensure changes to the bilateral aid budgets for (a) Rwanda, (b) Kenya and (c) Ghana do not affect poverty reduction in those countries.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","58525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663006","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>The UK was at the forefront of negotiating the Global Goals for Sustainable Development and we will be at the forefront of delivering them. We have implemented the Goals across all of Government’s work, the delivery of which is tracked through Single Departmental Plans.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-09T17:16:40.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663006/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663006/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663006/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Developing Countries: Sustainable Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps the Government is taking to ensure the Sustainable Development Goals are implemented in the UK.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","58519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663007","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>As the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) were launched in January 2016, it is too early to make an assessment of the effect of their implementation. However, the ambition of the SDGs to Leave No One Behind is clear.</p><p>The impact of the Sustainable Development Goals will be tracked through country data and systems for reporting using the SDGs.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-09T16:43:01.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663007/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663007/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663007/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Developing Countries: Sustainable Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made of the effect of the implementation of the Sustainable Development Goals on older women.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","58520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663008","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>We have radically transformed CDC over the last five years to ensure their investments are targeted where they are needed most and have greatest impact in the world’s poorest places.</p><p>Since 2012, all new investments made by CDC have been focussed on Africa and South Asia where 80% of the world’s poorest live, and where CDC investment can have the greatest development impact. All investments made by CDC are made in accordance with the Investment Policy agreed with DFID. This ensures that CDC invests responsibly and transparently, creating jobs and promoting good governance.</p><p>Through its Development Impact Grid, developed in conjunction with DFID, CDC is incentivised to specifically invest in the poorer countries and regions and across those sectors that have the highest propensity to create jobs, such as infrastructure, agribusiness and financial services. Creating jobs for the world’s poorest countries is a key driver in reducing poverty. In 2015, CDC-backed businesses helped create over a million new direct and indirect jobs (41% Africa and 59% South Asia).</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-09T17:00:03.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663008/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663008/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663008/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","CDC: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what mechanisms her Department has in place to ensure that spending of public funds by the Commonwealth Development Corporation is focused on the reduction of poverty.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","58567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663009","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Independent Commission on Aid Impact (ICAI) published a review of DFID’s approach to managing exit and transition in its development partnerships in November 2016. My Department will publish its response shortly to recommendations made in the ICAI report, including on cross-government management of relationships and risk, and on communication.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-09T16:51:16.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663009/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663009/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663009/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to improve relationship management with bilateral government partners through transition by risk management and more coordinated communications.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","58565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663010","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government has placed the Global Goals for Sustainable Development at the centre of its international development efforts and its UK Aid Strategy. The internal Business Plans of all relevant DFID departments and country offices include in their longer-term objectives how they will contribute to achieving the vision of the Global Goals.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-09T17:23:38.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663010/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663010/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663010/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Developing Countries: Sustainable Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that its policies focus on means to achieve the Sustainable Development Goals.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","58566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663011","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>All of DFID’s funding including for NGO’s is subject to rigorous review processes, including completion of annual performance reviews. Reports from these annual reviews and other project documentation are available on DFID’s Devtracker which can be found at https://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/</p><p>DFIDs Annual Report for 2015/16 was published on 13 July providing details of the results DFID achieved through a range of delivery partners. This can be found on our website at www.gov.uk/government/collections/dfid-annual-report-2011-2012</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-09T17:23:06.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663011/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663011/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663011/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Non-governmental Organisations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking regularly to report on its funding for non-governmental organisations.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","58556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663012","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>The UK is supportive of people-to-people (co-existence) programmes that bring Israelis and Palestinians together to break down barriers and build trust. Ministers are assessing options for how the UK can do more to support work in this area.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-09T16:52:43.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663012/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663012/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663012/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to support the creation of an international fund for Israeli-Palestinian peace.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","58557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663013","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>The National Security Council, of which the Secretary of State is a Member, is the main forum for collective discussion of the government’s objectives for national security, foreign policy and international development. The Secretary of State for International Development is also a member of the European Union Exit and Trade Committee, which oversees the negotiations on the withdrawal from the European Union and policy on international trade, the Committee for Tackling Extremism in Communities, and the Committee for Tackling Modern Slavery and People Trafficking.</p><p>Coordination at working level is provided by sub-groups and overseen by the Cabinet Office secretariats.</p><p>Overseas, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office is responsible for leading the UK’s relationship with the host country and for ensuring a coherent cross-government approach that reflects all government priorities, including development.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-09T16:54:31.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663013/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663013/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663013/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what mechanisms are in place within government to ensure that development considerations are taken account of in wider government bilateral relationships.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","58558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663014","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Independent Commission on Aid Impact (ICAI) published its review of DFID’s approach to managing exit and transition in its development partnerships in November 2016. My Department will shortly publish its response to recommendations made in the ICAI report, including the reporting of aid relationships following the end or transition of a DFID country programme.</p><p>DFID is a leader on aid transparency. The Secretary of State set out her vision for even greater transparency in the Bilateral and Multilateral Development Reviews published on 1 December. DFID will provide detail for how this can be achieved in due course.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-09T17:24:55.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663014/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663014/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663014/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to improve transparency and accountability on its commitments to end aid or change aid relationships.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","58559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663015","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>DFID is an active and engaged shareholder. Our influence over the strategic direction of CDC is evident from the changes that CDC has undergone over the last 5/6 years, in which we have played a key role.</p><p>DFID, as sole shareholder, sets the company’s investment policy – outlining which countries CDC should invest in, the types of investments it makes, and setting the performance targets CDC must reach. DFID appoints the Chair and certain other members of the Board, and holds the Board accountable for delivery of CDC’s five year strategy and for achieving the performance targets set in the Investment Policy.</p><p>Management has delegated authority from the Board to make investment decisions, meet corporate objectives and financial regulatory obligations.</p><p>DFID exercises shareholder oversight through close contact with both Board and management, including via Quarterly Shareholder Meetings held to review progress and performance (financial, development impact, risk management, investment pipeline forecasts) and Annual Meetings with the Board.</p><p>DFID’s oversight of CDC is scrutinised by the International Development Committee, the National Audit Office, UK Government Investments, the Treasury and the Public Accounts Committee. The National Audit Office recently described DFID’s governance arrangements as ‘thorough’ in its recent value for money study.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-09T16:57:43.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663015/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663015/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663015/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","CDC","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that it maintains accountability and oversight of the use of public funds by the Commonwealth Development Corporation.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","58560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663016","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>In programming new activities, DFID works with its partners to identify priorities and establish needs across the energy spectrum, covering on-grid as well as decentralised off-grid renewable energy.</p><p>All DFID projects are monitored through regular annual reviews, which are published on the development tracker section of the DFID website. For example, the Renewable Energy and Adaptation to Climate Technologies project has increased access to decentralised renewable energy for approximately 560,000 people in East Africa.</p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-09T17:11:49.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663016/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663016/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663016/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Developing Countries: Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made of the effect of UK aid expenditure on decentralised renewable energy on rural communities; and if she will make an assessment of the potential merits of increasing such aid expenditure.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","58401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663017","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>Leaving the EU means we will want to take our own decisions about how to deliver the policy objectives previously targeted by EU funding. Over the coming months we will consult closely with stakeholders to ensure that any ongoing funding commitments best serve the UK‘s national interest.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-09T17:16:12.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663017/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663017/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663017/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","EU Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether the Government plans to include future arrangements for the allocation of development funds previously distributed by EU institutions in its negotiation plan on leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","58442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663018","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>I can confirm my department currently does not have the facility to allow staff to join a credit union through payroll deductions. Staff can still make arrangements to contribute to a credit union via direct debit.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-09T17:25:25.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663018/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663018/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663018/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Department for International Development: Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department permits its employees to join a credit union through payroll deductions; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","58456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663019","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>The latest report of the Sustainable Energy For All Global Tracking Framework (coordinated by the World Bank and the International Energy Agency) estimates that 1.1 billion people, primarily in sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia, lacked reliable access to electricity in 2012. The report notes that progress towards the Sustainable Development Goal target of universal access to affordable, reliable and modern energy services by 2030 has accelerated. Faster progress is needed if the target is to be achieved, however.</p><p>DFID is working with our partners, including the World Bank, African Development Bank and Asian Development Bank, to raise and channel the public and private finance needed to reach the target.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-09T17:01:25.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663019/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663019/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663019/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Developing Countries: Electricity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many people globally she estimates (a) are without reliable access to electricity and (b) will be without reliable access to electricity in 2030.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","58409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663020","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-13","<p>The attached spreadsheet shows the:</p><p> </p><ul><li>average length of sentence for people convicted of using an impersonator to take the written and practical driving test in each of the last five years and by geographical location, and the</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>average length of sentence for people convicted of impersonating a candidate and taking the written and practical driving test in each of the last five years and by geographical location.</li></ul><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","58402","2017-01-13T10:46:35.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663020/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663020/answer","058402, 058405 - Average Length of Sentence - Driving Tests.xlsx","Diving Test  - Statistics","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663020/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Driving Tests: Personation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the average length of sentence was for people convicted of impersonating a candidate and taking the (a) written and (b) practical parts of the driving test for them in each of the last five years and by geographical area.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","58405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663021","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-27","<p>MoJ does not currently have a policy to provide access to credit union services through payroll deductions. We will however be monitoring arrangements in DWP with a view to determining whether MoJ should develop such a policy as part of its wider wellbeing strategy. MoJ is also in the process of implementing a new cross-government benefits platform which in addition to providing access to salary sacrifice benefits and discounts on goods and services also provides staff with information to raise financial awareness.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-01-27T14:18:40.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663021/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663021/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663021/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-20","Ministry of Justice: Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether her Department permits its employees to join a credit union through payroll deductions; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","58458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663022","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-13","<p>The attached spreadsheet shows the:</p><p> </p><ul><li>average length of sentence for people convicted of using an impersonator to take the written and practical driving test in each of the last five years and by geographical location, and the</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>average length of sentence for people convicted of impersonating a candidate and taking the written and practical driving test in each of the last five years and by geographical location.</li></ul><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","58405","2017-01-13T10:46:35.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663022/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663022/answer","058402, 058405 - Average Length of Sentence - Driving Tests.xlsx","Diving Test  - Statistics","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663022/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Driving Tests: Personation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the average length of sentence was for people convicted of using an impersonator to take the (a) written and (b) practical parts of the driving test for them in each of the last five years and by geographical area.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","58402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663023","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-18","<p>The deadline for responses was 6 January 2017. The government is satisfied that this gave those with an interest in the proposed reforms sufficient time to respond.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-04-18T15:20:08.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663023/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663023/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663023/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-20","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will extend the duration of her Department's consultation on Reforming the Soft Tissue Injury (Whiplash) Claims Process to take account of the Christmas period.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","58491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663024","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-31","<p>Assessments of the likely equality impacts and of the potential economic costs and benefits of provision for marriages by non-religious belief organisations, including humanist marriages, were published on gov.uk in June 2014 in the consultation paper on such provision.</p><p> </p><p>The Law Commission has published its report on initial scoping work to identify the issues for potential reform of the law concerning how and where people can get married in England and Wales. The Government is carefully considering the report and will respond in due course.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-01-31T16:21:05.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663024/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663024/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663024/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-20","Marriage: Humanism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to section 14 of the Marriage (Same Sex) Couples Act 2013, what recent assessment her Department has made of the potential merits of legalising humanist marriages; and whether the Government has plans to bring forward legislative proposals to legalise such marriages.","false","Biography information for Naz Shah","Bradford West","Naz Shah","58588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663025","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Northern Ireland Office currently does not have a policy to provide access to credit union services through payroll deductions. Staff can however make arrangements to contribute to a credit union via direct debit.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2017-01-09T11:48:11.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663025/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663025/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663025/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-12-20","Northern Ireland Office: Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, whether his Department permits its employees to join a credit union through payroll deductions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","58459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663026","Prime Minister","false","2017-01-13","<p>Information covering the period from July to September 2016 was published on 21 December 2016 and is available on the gov.uk website.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-01-13T09:36:33.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663026/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663026/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663026/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-12-20","Prime Minister: Meetings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, when information on her external meetings from July to September 2016 will be published.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","58547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663027","Scotland Office","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Scotland Office does not employ staff directly. Matters relating to the terms and conditions of service of staff, including information in relation to payroll deductions of staff are matters for the employing bodies.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-01-11T13:14:04.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663027/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663027/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663027/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-12-20","Scotland Office: Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, whether his Department permits its employees to join a credit union through payroll deductions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","58460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663028","Scotland Office","false","2017-01-11","<p>I visited a foodbank in my capacity as a Member of Parliament earlier in this parliamentary term.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The reasons behind foodbank use are complex and it is widely acknowledged that food bank use cannot be attributed to a single cause. The UK Government is clear that work is the best route out of poverty, and the number of people in employment in Scotland is up by 123,000 since 2010. The Scottish Government now hold the main levers to shape and strengthen the economy in Scotland, as well as taking responsibility for significant policy choices in relation to welfare.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","58429","2017-01-11T13:15:44.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663028/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663028/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663028/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-12-20","Food Banks: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what plans he has to visit a food bank in January 2017.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","58430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663029","Scotland Office","false","2017-01-11","<p>I visited a foodbank in my capacity as a Member of Parliament earlier in this parliamentary term.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The reasons behind foodbank use are complex and it is widely acknowledged that food bank use cannot be attributed to a single cause. The UK Government is clear that work is the best route out of poverty, and the number of people in employment in Scotland is up by 123,000 since 2010. The Scottish Government now hold the main levers to shape and strengthen the economy in Scotland, as well as taking responsibility for significant policy choices in relation to welfare.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","58430","2017-01-11T13:15:44.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663029/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663029/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663029/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-12-20","Food Banks: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, whether he has visited a food bank in December 2016.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","58429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663030","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-13","<p>I am responsible for cycling and will be meeting with the All-Party Parliamentary Cycling Group in the next few weeks.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-01-13T09:54:25.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663030/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663030/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663030/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Cycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will meet the All-Party Parliamentary Cycling Group to discuss issues facing cyclists in London and elsewhere.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","58357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663031","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-13","<p>The incident was not reported to the police. At the time of the incident, my Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State checked the cyclist was okay and waited until he was back on his feet. He spoke to the cyclist and apologised; they shook hands. No details were requested at the time by either party who then went their separate ways.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-01-13T10:02:42.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663031/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663031/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663031/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Cycling: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he, his driver or any official reported to the police the incident on 12 October 2016 in which a cyclist came off his bike.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","58358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663032","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-13","<p>No assessment has been made.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-01-13T09:46:50.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663032/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663032/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663032/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Cycling: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of section 42 of the Road Traffic Act 1988 in protecting cyclists.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","58352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663033","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA), the Agency responsible for practical and theory driving tests, is unable to estimate the number of people who currently hold a driving licence fraudulently obtained by using an impersonator to take the (a) written and (b) practical parts of the driving test for them.</p><p> </p><p>The DVSA does however has a dedicated Counter-Fraud and Investigation Team which actively investigates instances of fraud, including impersonation at theory and practical driving tests. DVSA has also recently launched a 3-year counter fraud strategy. One aspect of the strategy is to prevent the fraudulent issue of licences or the circumvention of controls as part of the delivery of DVSA products and services; ensuring they are only accessible by those who are eligible or entitled to them. The strategy also aims to prosecute and disrupt those individuals and organisations suspected of submitting fraudulent applications or of being complicit in criminal activity.</p><p> </p><p>Over the last five years over 1,100 licences have been revoked due to evidence that the licence was obtained fraudulently, which includes impersonation.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-01-13T10:22:40.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663033/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663033/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663033/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Driving: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department has made of the number of people who currently hold a driving licence fraudulently obtained by using an impersonator to take the (a) written and (b) practical parts of the driving test for them.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","58408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663034","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-13","<p>I can confirm my department currently does not have the facility to allow staff to join a credit union through payroll deductions. Staff can still make arrangements to contribute to a credit union via direct debit.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-13T10:11:53.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663034/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663034/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663034/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Department for Transport: Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department permits its employees to join a credit union through payroll deductions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","58461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663035","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-09","<p>My Department has not published anything related to Departmental Pool Car charges on 17 December 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The Departmental Pool Car is managed by individual Departments and individual trips are not logged.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-09T11:11:40.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663035/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663035/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663035/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Attorney General: Official Cars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the charges for Departmental Pool Car Service Charges to the Attorney General's Office between 2012 and 2015, published by his Department on 17 December 2016, what the (a) purpose, (b) distance travelled and (c) cost was of each journey booked by his office.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","58492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663036","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-09","<p>We cannot be certain about the timing of the publication of draft flight paths for an expanded Heathrow Airport, because the airport operator will be leading the application for the airspace changes needed for new flight paths associated with a new runway. They will need to follow the Civil Aviation Authority’s airspace change process. It is through this process that communities will see and have the opportunity to comment on detailed proposals for any new flight paths. This process covers all aspects of the proposal including safety and environmental impacts, and a requirement to consult the communities that may be affected by the proposal.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-09T16:52:05.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663036/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663036/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663036/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the timetable is for the publication of draft flight paths to and from an expanded Heathrow Airport.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","58498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663037","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-09","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the oral statement on airport capacity on 25 October 2016<strong>: </strong><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/airport-capacity" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/airport-capacity</a>. In that statement my Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State set out how the announcement fits within the planning process, and the opportunities members of this House have to contribute.</p><p> </p><p>He stated that in the New Year, we will bring forward a draft ‘National policy statement’, which includes the details of the proposed scheme.</p><p> </p><p>As required under legislation, this will be subject to a full and extensive public consultation, followed by a period of Parliamentary scrutiny.</p><p> </p><p>Only once members have voted on the final National Policy Statement and it has been designated will the airport be able to bring forward a detailed planning application.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-09T10:56:06.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663037/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663037/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663037/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to publish the draft National Policy Statement on the expansion of Heathrow Airport.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","58488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663038","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government has been clear that the promoter, Heathrow Airport Limited, will meet the costs of the surface access improvements necessary to allow expansion of the airport.</p><p> </p><p>Where a surface access scheme has a wider range of beneficiaries, and are not specific to the addition of a new runway, the Government will consider, along with other relevant stakeholders, the need for public funding on a case-by-case basis.</p><p> </p><p>For schemes such as the Western Rail Link and Southern Rail Access, such considerations would take place at an appropriate time in that project’s development process.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-09T10:48:46.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663038/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663038/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663038/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to announce which elements of surface access to the proposed third runway at Heathrow Airport will be funded from the public purse.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","58487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663039","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-10","<p>Network Rail, as the infrastructure provider, is best placed to assess power supply resilience.</p><p> </p><p>Network Rail’s signalling power supplies are treated by the National grid as a priority. As such the standard provision for signalling centres on most parts of the network including railway operating centres are classified as part of an essential services distribution board. These are backed up by a fixed diesel generator and an uninterruptible power supply.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-01-10T15:49:38.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663039/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663039/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663039/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Railway Signals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the (a) resilience of power supply arrangements to railway signalling centres and (b) provision of back-up power supplies in the event of National Grid failures.","false","Biography information for Mrs Flick Drummond","Portsmouth South","Mrs Flick Drummond","58431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663040","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-09","<p>The economic benefits of a new runway at Heathrow have been assessed at a national level. It is estimated that a new runway will deliver up to £61 billion of benefits to passengers and the wider UK economy.</p><p> </p><p>The local jobs created at and around the airport have also been assessed, with Heathrow expansion expected to deliver up to 77,000 additional local jobs by 2030. While it is not possible to precisely quantify the impacts on regional jobs and GDP, expanding airport capacity in the South East will support economic growth in the UK’s regions.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-09T16:56:51.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663040/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663040/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663040/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the potential (a) economic benefits and (b) level of new jobs resulting from the third runway at Heathrow Airport by region of the UK.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","58484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663041","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-09","<p>The bus market outside London is deregulated and decisions regarding the provision of individual bus services is a matter for individual operators, or for individual local authorities in the case of services they support. It is for them to decide how to consult with passengers prior to making any changes. Best practice advice is available in the Transport Focus publication “Bus service reviews: consulting on changes to local services - A best practice toolkit&quot;.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-01-09T15:14:52.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663041/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663041/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663041/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Bus Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what guidance his Department issues on standards of consultations prior to bus route changes; and whether there is a requirement in that guidance that passenger number surveys are conducted on multiple days of the week at multiple times of the day.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","58593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663042","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-09","<p>Part of the scope of the Sheffield to Rotherham tram train pilot project is the production of a suite of information on the lessons learned during both the design and delivery phases of the project. This information will be published for the benefit of interested parties. The project team is also available to provide advice and have supplied information to a number of cities in the United Kingdom.</p><p> </p><p>I understand that the tram train project team have been in contact with the Glasgow Airport Access Project team since autumn 2015 and have shared learning and experience relevant to the early development of that scheme. This has included information on vehicle characteristics and operational interfaces. The Glasgow team have also visited Sheffield to gain direct experience of the tram train vehicles.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-01-09T11:59:19.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663042/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663042/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663042/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Trams","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what lessons his Department learned from the Sheffield to Rotherham tram-train pilot; and what steps he is taking to apply those lessons in the proposed tram-train to Glasgow Airport project.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","58628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663043","Wales Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>The Wales Office is not an employer in its own right. Staff are generally employed by the Ministry of Justice (MoJ). MoJ currently does not have a policy to provide access to credit union services through payroll deductions.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2017-01-12T13:05:31.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663043/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663043/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663043/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-12-20","Wales Office: Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, whether his Department permits its employees to join a credit union through payroll deductions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","58462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663044","Women and Equalities","false","2017-01-24","<p>The department does not currently offer the facility for employees to join a credit union through payroll deductions. We will be considering whether to introduce this as part of our offer to staff.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-24T17:48:58.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663044/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663044/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663044/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-12-20","Government Equalities Office: Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, whether the Government Equalities Office permits its employees to join a credit union through payroll deductions; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","58453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663045","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-11","<p>On 6th July 2016 DWP launched a payroll savings scheme to allow staff to access financial services delivered by three partner credit unions - Commsave, Hull and East Yorkshire, and Voyager Alliance - directly through payroll. This initiative formed part of DWP’s “Working Well Together” wellbeing programme. Early indications are that the scheme has been very well received and so far over 2,100 DWP staff have signed up as credit union members through payroll.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-01-11T16:59:05.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663045/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663045/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663045/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Department for Work and Pensions: Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department permits its employees to join a credit union through payroll deductions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","58463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663046","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-10","<p>There is no record of any visits to Bridgeton Jobcentre Plus.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-10T14:17:55.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663046/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663046/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663046/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, on which date a Minister of his Department last visited Bridgeton Jobcentre Plus in Glasgow.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","58428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663047","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Pension Protection Fund (PPF) is an independent body which pays compensation to members of defined benefit occupational pension schemes where the sponsoring employer becomes insolvent and the scheme is unable to cover the accrued pension liabilities. The PPF is funded from a combination of the transferred scheme funds, recoveries from the insolvent employer, investment return and a levy on eligible schemes.</p><p> </p><p>Under the Pensions Act 2004, the levy is set by the PPF independently of the Government.</p><p>I have received one letter regarding the impact of the Pension Protection Fund levy on retail co-operatives, which I referred to the PPF for a reply.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-01-09T15:53:46.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663047/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663047/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663047/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Pension Protection Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many representations he has received on the effect of the Pension Protection Fund Levy on retail co-operatives; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","58436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663048","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-01-09T16:12:29.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663048/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663048/answer","CO-DC00-PRN01_Rayhan Ali_4231_001.pdf","UKSA Response to PQ58421","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663048/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-20","Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 10 November 2016 to Question 51658, when he expects the UK Statistics Authority to place its additional analysis in the Library.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","58421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663049","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Office for Budget Responsibility produces the official economic forecasts for HM Government.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-11T16:50:46.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663049/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663049/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663049/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Construction: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of trends in employment in the construction sector over the next five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","58366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663050","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-13","<p>This Department does not hold this information.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-13T14:37:39.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663050/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663050/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663050/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Food Banks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information his Department holds on the use of three-day emergency food parcels.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","58354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663051","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-10","<p>As announced by the Secretary of State on 21 November 2016, the proposals for the future funding of supported housing are currently subject to public consultation. The consultation document was published on 21 November 2016 and closes on 13 February 2017.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-10T14:13:30.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663051/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663051/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663051/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Local Housing Allowance: Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will review his Department's plans to cap housing benefit for those in supported housing in line with local housing allowance.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","58369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663052","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-10","<p>The Department is willing to meet with the PCS if they request it.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-10T15:14:42.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663052/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663052/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663052/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Social Security Benefits: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 15 December 2016 to Question 56948, if his Department will meet the PCS union in January 2017 to discuss social security benefits for children.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","58591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663053","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-10","<p>Following the initial announcement we undertake a site level Equality Analysis, which covers both customers and colleagues, to enable us to pay due regard to people impacted by the change who have a protected characteristic under the Equality Act 2010.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the number of staff supporting customers isn’t decreasing. Our proposal means we will be able to deliver enhanced services by bringing together some neighbouring jobcentres in Glasgow where we can achieve access to more employers and partners.</p><p> </p><p>Increasingly, our customers access many of our services on-line. This includes claiming benefits, looking for jobs and keeping us informed of their efforts to find work. We tailor our service so that face-to-face contact can be focused on those who need extra support from us.</p><p> </p><p>We have also agreed that where the distance from the current location to the proposed alternative jobcentre is over three miles or 20 minutes away by public transport, we are undertaking a public consultation to inform our final decisions on closure and alternative service delivery options.</p><p> </p><p>We started this consultation on 7 December 2016 which includes information on the gov.uk website. The consultation will close on 31 January 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Finally, employment is not just a DWP agenda and we will continue to work with Skills Development Scotland, the Scottish Government, local authorities and other partner organisations to provide access to employment opportunities.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-10T14:39:00.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663053/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663053/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663053/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the proposed jobcentre closures in Glasgow on levels of deprivation in (a) Glasgow South constituency and (b) the city of Glasgow.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","58473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663054","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-10","<p>We are committed to continuing to serve people in all areas of the country to make sure that they can continue to access the services they need.</p><p> </p><p>We started a consultation process for the proposed closure of some Glasgow jobcentres on 7 December 2016 and have posted information on the Gov.uk website.</p><p> </p><p>The consultation will close on 31 January 2017.</p><p> </p><p>We will explain what any changes will mean for people using our services nearer to any agreed moves.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-10T14:25:27.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663054/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663054/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663054/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent discussions he has had with third sector organisations on the proposed jobcentre closures in Glasgow.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","58472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663055","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-10","<p>No national insurance numbers have been issued by Jobcentres in Castlemilk and Langside in the past 12 months.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-10T14:41:56.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663055/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663055/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663055/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","National Insurance: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many national insurance numbers have been issued by jobcentres in (a) Castlemilk and (b) Langside in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","58474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663056","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-10","<p>We will be undertaking an equality analysis as part of the detailed planning for service reconfiguration. This will include feedback from public consultation in those locations where this applies.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-10T14:45:25.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663056/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663056/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663056/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to provide an equality impact assessment in relation to the proposed jobcentre closures in Glasgow.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","58475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663057","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-10","<p>In relation to elected representatives, the Minister for employment wrote to the elected representatives from Glasgow on 7 December to inform them of the proposals and subsequently met with them on Thursday 15<sup>th</sup> December to discuss plans and hear views to ensure final proposals offer the best service possible for the people of Glasgow. On 20<sup>th</sup> December the Minister for Employment attended a Westminster Hall Debate on the proposals.</p><p> </p><p>In terms of staff representation, this will be twofold, firstly via the affiliated Departmental Trade Unions and secondly, staff will have the opportunity to participate in 1-2-1 discussions with their managers. These conversations are already underway.</p><p> </p><p>Representatives from local organisations can choose to respond to the proposals by participating in the consultation process, details of which are available on gov.uk and this will be open until 31 January 2016. Additionally, they may chose to respond when engaging in normal partnership activities.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-10T14:55:04.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663057/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663057/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663057/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans he has to meet with representatives of the eight jobcentres in Glasgow earmarked for closure before his Department's public consultation ends on 31 January 2017.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","58476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663058","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-10","<p>The information is provided in the table below.</p><p> </p><p>Estimated breakdown of households affected by the lower cap levels by benefit receipt, 2016/17<br></p><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="2"><p><strong>Benefit Received</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Proportion of capped households</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Hounslow, (London borough of)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Employment and Support Allowance</p></td><td><p>18%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Income Support</p></td><td><p>46%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jobseeker's Allowance</p></td><td><p>20%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other</p></td><td><p>16%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Housing Benefit Only</p></td><td><p>0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>These estimates focus on the benefit cap continuing to be applied under Housing Benefit. The benefit cap will increasingly be applied under Universal Credit as it gradually rolls out. Universal Credit will replace Income Support, income-based Jobseeker's Allowance, income-based Employment and Support Allowance and Housing Benefit, along with Child Tax Credit and Working Tax Credit.</p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><ol><li>Figures may not sum due to rounding.</li><li>Estimates assume no behavioural responses - any behavioural responses to the lower cap, such as claimants moving into employment, would cause the number of households affected to reduce and may change the proportional split.</li><li>The methodology used to estimate the households affected by the cap is consistent with that described in the latest impact assessment published here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/welfare-reform-and-work-act-impact-assessment-for-the-benefit-cap" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/welfare-reform-and-work-act-impact-assessment-for-the-benefit-cap</a></li></ol><p> </p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-10T13:58:07.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663058/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663058/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663058/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Social Security Benefits: Hounslow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of claimants affected by the lower benefit caps in Hounslow are in receipt of (a) jobseeker's allowance, (b) employment and support allowance, (c) income support, (d) another benefit and (e) housing benefit alone.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","58512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663059","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-09","<p>The information is not available.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-09T16:06:08.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663059/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663059/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663059/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Department for Work and Pensions: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much his Department and any of its arms-length departmental bodies have spent on (a) staffing, (b) other revenue costs and (c) capital expenditure in the current fiscal year in Yorkshire and the Humber.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","58502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663060","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-10","<p>In Universal Credit Live service, as the claimant does not have access to the claim information themselves via an online account, we have implied consent arrangements in place so that someone can act on a claimants behalf. In Universal Credit Full Service, the online account allows claimant’s access to their information - a claimant can specify explicit consent at any time via the online account or on the phone, so an advocate can enquire on their behalf. Instructions to operational staff reflect these arrangements.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-10T15:10:37.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663060/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663060/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663060/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Universal Credit: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what instructions are given to staff working on the universal credit enquiry lines on protocols concerning the disclosure of personal data to third parties who have implicit consent from the claimant.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","58511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663061","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-09","<p>We will be undertaking an equality analysis as part of the detailed planning for service reconfiguration. This will include feedback from public consultation in those locations where this applies.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-09T16:03:11.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663061/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663061/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663061/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the Government has conducted an Equality Impact Assessment to evaluate the effect that the closure of Jobcentre Plus offices will have in Glasgow.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","58624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663062","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-10","<p>Consumers who have entered Green Deal Plans will continue to be covered by the Green Deal Framework even if their Green Deal Provider has gone into liquidation. This means that the plan repayments will continue as normal, with no disruption in service.</p><p>Where consumers have a concern, they can still make any complaints to the Green Deal Ombudsman or the Financial Services Ombudsman (FOS) as appropriate, even though the Green Deal Provider is in liquidation.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-10T11:37:37.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663062/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663062/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663062/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-20","Green Deal Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what support the Government provides to people who received Green Deal finance from a company that has since gone into liquidation.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","58549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663063","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Department is aware that some customers of the Green Deal Provider, Home Energy &amp; Lifestyle Management Ltd (HELMS), have made allegations that they were mis-sold their Green Deal plans by HELMS. In November 2015, my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State imposed sanctions on HELMS for breaches of the Green Deal Code of Practice. HELMS has since gone into liquidation. It would not be appropriate to comment on individual cases at this stage. However, customers who have complaints about their plans should raise these with the Green Deal Ombudsman or Financial Ombudsman Service as appropriate.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-11T12:54:17.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663063/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663063/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663063/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-20","Green Deal Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what representations his Department has received from consumers on the sale of Green Deal services by Home Energy and Lifestyle Management Ltd.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","58548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663064","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government has always stated that the mis-selling of financial products is wrong, and it is important that businesses that have been affected should be compensated.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is an independent non-governmental body responsible for regulating and supervising the financial services industry. The FCA does not have general regulatory powers over business lending.</p><p> </p><p>As a result, the redress scheme covering the mis-selling of interest rate hedging products (IRHPs) only covers those products that were agreed separately to a business loan. Some banks voluntarily carried out their own reviews on the sale of fixed rate loans with characteristics of IRHPs, and have sought to mirror the IRHP redress scheme process.</p><p> </p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","58582","2017-01-09T14:29:13.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663064/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663064/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663064/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-20","Business: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps have been taken to aid those firms affected by the mis-selling of synthetic fixed-rate loans between 2001 and 2009.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","58617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663065","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-10","<p>The Government has already made progress towards the targeted reduction of CO2 emissions by 2030 - provisional statistics indicate that UK emissions in 2015 were 38% lower than in 1990.</p><p>We are looking ahead to our emissions reduction plan which will set out how we will reduce emissions through the 2020s and so form an important signal to the markets, businesses and investors.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-10T11:37:56.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663065/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663065/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663065/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-20","Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 25 October 2016 to Question 47955, what steps his Department has taken to ensure that the targeted reduction of CO2 emissions to 57 per cent of 1990 levels by 2030 is met.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","58581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663066","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government has always stated that the mis-selling of financial products is wrong, and it is important that businesses that have been affected should be compensated.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is an independent non-governmental body responsible for regulating and supervising the financial services industry. The FCA does not have general regulatory powers over business lending.</p><p> </p><p>As a result, the redress scheme covering the mis-selling of interest rate hedging products (IRHPs) only covers those products that were agreed separately to a business loan. Some banks voluntarily carried out their own reviews on the sale of fixed rate loans with characteristics of IRHPs, and have sought to mirror the IRHP redress scheme process.</p><p> </p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","58617","2017-01-09T14:29:13.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663066/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663066/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663066/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-20","Business: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps the Government has taken to assist people affected by the mis-selling of synthetic fixed-rate loans between 2001 and 2009.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","58582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663067","Department for Education","false","2017-01-25","<p>English language colleges are independent organisations that are responsible for their own staffing. My department does not hold any information on the numbers of people employed in such organisations in England.</p><p>As education is a devolved matter, any assessment of English language college’s staff numbers outside of England is a matter for the relevant devolved authorities.</p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-01-25T14:06:58.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663067/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663067/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663067/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-20","English Language: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information her Department holds on the number of people employed in English language colleges in each region and constituent part of the UK.","false","Biography information for Paul Scully","Sutton and Cheam","Paul Scully","58544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663068","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government has set out its plans for the sale of the Green Investment Bank in the document “Green Investment Bank: sale of shares” (Cm 9214) laid before Parliament on 3 March 2016. As set out in that report, one of the Government’s primary objectives for a sale is to achieve value for money for the UK taxpayer.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-01-09T15:05:38.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663068/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663068/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663068/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-20","Green Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will make it his policy to ensure that any proceeds from the sale of the Green Investment Bank are greater than or equivalent to the 10 per cent portfolio return forecast by that Bank in its latest Annual Report.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","58384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663069","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) was created on 14 July 2016. The Department of Energy and Climate Change (DECC) and the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) were merged to create this new department.</p><p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy does not currently have the facility for staff to join a credit union through payroll deductions.</p><p>Some Government departments offer this facility and it is currently being looked into by the central civil service HR team. Once a decision has been made, BEIS will consider these recommendations as part of its ongoing work to ensure staff are offered a benefits package that is current and reflective of the wider Civil Service.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-09T15:01:18.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663069/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663069/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663069/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-20","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether his Department permits its employees to join a credit union through payroll deductions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","58443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663070","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Department for International Trade supports over 400 events and missions annually and has a presence at major trade shows overseas to support UK companies, including new British exporters. At these events meeting areas and networking facilities are available to help businesses promote their goods/services.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-01-13T13:49:42.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663070/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663070/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663070/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-20","Trade Promotion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps his Department is taking to offer support to new exporters with meeting areas and networking facilities at overseas exhibitions.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","58410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663071","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-13","<p>GREAT Club was launched in January 2014. It is an invitation-only service, providing leading business executives with bespoke immigration support.</p><p>In November 2016, the Prime Minister announced that the Indian Government will be able to nominate GREAT club members. This agreement reinforces the Government's commitment to strengthen trading ties with all corners of the globe as the UK leaves the EU and demonstrates both governments’ commitment to building the closest possible trade and economic relationship between the two countries.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-01-13T12:42:27.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663071/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663071/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663071/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-20","Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on international trade policy of the Prime Minister's announcement of the creation of the GREAT club bespoke visa and immigration service.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","58411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663072","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Chemical Industry Association estimates the chemical sector is worth £15 billion annually to the UK economy.</p><p> </p><p>As the Prime Minster has stated, we want British companies to have the maximum freedom to trade with and operate in the Single Market – and to let European businesses to do the same here.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for International Trade, colleagues in BEIS and others have regular discussions with representatives of the British coatings industry. Delegates from DIT, BEIS, HSE and DEFRA, who are responsible for regulation and standards for the sector, recently participated in a round-table discussion on the UK leaving the EU organised by the British Coatings Federation (BCF) and attended by a number of companies from the sector.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-01-13T13:39:58.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663072/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663072/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663072/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-20","UK Trade with EU: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of the potential access of British coatings companies to European markets after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","58412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663073","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Department for International Trade’s International trade and Investment team (ITI), which assumed the responsibilities of UKTI in July 2016, undertakes a yearly client survey of businesses to measure the quality and impact of our services. In financial year 2015-16:</p><ul><li>65% of businesses attending DIT Trade Shows and Missions expected their attendance to result in a positive financial benefit. On average, businesses anticipated additional export sales of £331,000 as a direct result of this activity.</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>For those attending DIT-sponsored Events, 41% of businesses expected a positive financial benefit. On average, businesses anticipated additional export sales of £611,000 per business as a result of attending Events organised with the support of the Department.</li></ul>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-01-13T13:42:39.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663073/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663073/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663073/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-20","UK Trade and Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of the relative commercial success of UKTI sponsored multi-industry market visits and industry-specific events since his Department was created.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","58413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663074","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Department for International Trade, and other departments including DExEU, BEIS, DEFRA and HSE, have had extensive discussions with representatives from both UK based chemicals companies and trade bodies such as the Chemical Industries Association, the British Coatings Federation and others at both Ministerial and official level. The Department will continue to hold such discussions, as it does with many sector representatives.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-01-13T13:37:41.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663074/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663074/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663074/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-20","UK Trade with EU: Chemicals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what representations his Department has received from chemical companies based in the UK on their access to EU markets after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","58414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663075","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-13","<p>As the Prime Minster has stated, we want British companies to have the maximum freedom to trade with, and operate in the Single Market – and to let European businesses do the same here - including the trade in the REACH regulated chemicals used in coatings and inks after the UK leaves the EU.</p><p>DIT is in regular discussion with others across Whitehall to help ensure this is the case. This includes colleagues in DEFRA and HSE who are responsible for regulation and standards for the sector.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-01-13T14:00:39.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663075/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663075/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663075/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-20","UK Trade with EU: Chemicals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he plans to take to ensure that British industries dependent on the REACH regulation to import raw materials for coatings and inks will be able to import the materials they need after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","58415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663076","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-13","<p>I refer the hon Member for East Antrim to the answer I gave to the hon Member for Copeland on 11 November 2016, UIN: 52613.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-01-13T14:17:33.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663076/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663076/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663076/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-20","Trade Agreements: Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what plans his Department has to make use of the proposed expansion of Heathrow Airport and potential new long-haul air links arising from that expansion in negotiating future trade agreements.","false","Biography information for Sammy Wilson","East Antrim","Sammy Wilson","58465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663077","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-13","<p>I can confirm my department currently does not have the facility to allow staff to join a credit union through payroll deductions. Staff can still make arrangements to contribute to a credit union via direct debit.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-01-13T11:39:56.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663077/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663077/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663077/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-20","Department for International Trade: Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether his Department permits its employees to join a credit union through payroll deductions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","58457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663078","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) has three dedicated staff in Tanzania. Tanzania is part of the ‘High Level Partnerships Programme’ which promotes cross-government coordination of trade support. In addition, high level support for specific commercial opportunities is provided by the Prime Minister’s Trade Envoy for Tanzania, Lord Hollick.</p><p>DIT Tanzania is involved in three high value campaigns, those for oil &amp; gas, infrastructure and renewables. The current pipeline includes at least £500m worth of potential UK export success over the next five years.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-01-13T14:03:35.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663078/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663078/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663078/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-20","Overseas Trade: Tanzania","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps the Government is taking to promote trade between the UK and Tanzania.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","58362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663079","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-10","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) has a dedicated trade promotion officer in Zambia. In addition, trade promotion activity across Southern Africa is coordinated regionally through the ‘hub’ in Johannesburg from where additional support is provided, including sector-specific expertise.</p><p>DIT provides support to UK companies considering investment in Zambia, ranging from oil and gas exploration to sustainable farming opportunities. In 2016, the Department, delivered a Mining Mission to Zambia, linking UK-based businesses with Zambian counterparts. Furthermore, a British Chamber of Commerce has been established which provides support for British companies seeking business opportunities in Zambia.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-01-10T13:13:48.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663079/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663079/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663079/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-20","Overseas Trade: Zambia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps the Government is taking to promote trade between the UK and Zambia.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","58363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663080","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) offer a range of export services to UK firms. These include actively seeking out opportunities for UK firms in each market; conducting market research and leading market visits. In February 2016, there was a security &amp; defence market visit to Jamaica. The Department are planning further events such as a UK food and beverage regional event in collaboration with the GREAT campaign for later this year. In St Lucia, DIT has worked to promote the interests of UK companies, particularly in the infrastructure sectors.</p><p>For Montserrat and Anguilla, we have reiterated our commitment to ensuring that the Territories reach their full potential as open, dynamic and sustainable economies, delivering growth, prosperity and employment for their citizens.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-01-13T14:10:23.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663080/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663080/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663080/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-20","Overseas Trade: Caribbean","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps the Government is taking to promote trade between the UK and (a) Jamaica, (b) St Lucia and (c) Montserrat and Anguilla.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","58364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663081","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-10","<p>Until the UK leaves the EU, we will remain subject to EU trade &amp; investment agreements and policy, of which human rights is a fundamental principle. The UK has a strong history of protecting human rights and promoting our values globally. We will in due course consider all options in the design of future bilateral trade and investment agreements.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","58571","2017-01-10T13:00:47.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663081/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663081/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663081/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-20","Overseas Trade: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he is taking to ensure that human rights considerations are included in the negotiation of future international trade and investment agreements.","false","Biography information for Sammy Wilson","East Antrim","Sammy Wilson","58572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663082","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-10","<p>Until the UK leaves the EU, we will remain subject to EU trade &amp; investment agreements and policy, of which human rights is a fundamental principle. The UK has a strong history of protecting human rights and promoting our values globally. We will in due course consider all options in the design of future bilateral trade and investment agreements.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","58572","2017-01-10T13:00:47.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663082/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663082/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663082/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-20","Overseas Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether he plans to include the issue of corporate responsibility to respect human rights in international investment agreements after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Sammy Wilson","East Antrim","Sammy Wilson","58571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663083","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-13","<p>I refer the hon Member to the answer given by my hon Friend for Broxtowe (Anna Soubry), the then Minister of State for Small Business, Industry and Enterprise, to the hon Member for Leeds Central on 4 May, UIN 36102.</p><p>Since this answer was provided a further 10 Standard Individual Export Licence applications have been refused under Criterion 2.</p><p>Licences granted and refused are published as Official Statistics, on a quarterly basis, at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.gov.uk</a>.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-01-13T12:56:23.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663083/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663083/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663083/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-20","Arms Trade: Export Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many licence applications have been refused under Criterion 2c of the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria in each year since 2008; and what the destination country was of each of those applications so refused.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","58546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663084","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-13","<p>As the proposed UK schedules will replicate the UK obligations contained in the current EU schedules and not alter the scope of UK concessions the Government intends to follow the WTO rectification procedures established, in 1980, for goods, and 1999, for services.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-01-13T12:46:41.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663084/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663084/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663084/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-20","World Trade Organisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what his policy is on whether the UK's schedules of concessions and commitments will be submitted to the WTO as modifications or as rectifications after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","58537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663085","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-10","<p>The annual budget for the GREAT Britain campaign is £60million.</p><p>To date, the campaign has secured confirmed economic returns of £2.2bn for the UK, a return of 20:1 on investment. A further £2.1bn is currently being independently audited. The National Audit Office recently reviewed and commended the campaign.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-01-10T13:54:14.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663085/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663085/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663085/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-20","Trade Promotion: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the annual budget is for the GREAT campaign.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","58539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663086","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-13","<p>As the Government prepares UK-specific WTO schedules, it is the intention of the Government not to alter the scope of UK obligations, or the concessions currently enjoyed by WTO members.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-01-13T11:00:31.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663086/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663086/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663086/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-20","World Trade Organisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, with reference to his Written Ministerial Statement of 5 December 2016, HCWS316, how the planned UK-specific WTO schedules he announced in his 5 December statement will differ from the UK's existing obligations.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","58538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663087","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-13","<p>All Government Departments are bound by legal requirements concerning the right to work in the UK and, in addition, the Civil Service Nationality Rules. Evidence of nationality is checked at the point of recruitment into the Civil Service as part of wider pre-employment checks, but there is no requirement on departments to retain this information beyond the point at which it has served its purpose. Once employed, employees are invited to disclose their nationality, however this is entirely voluntary. As such, there are no total figures for the department that can be provided.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-01-13T11:50:03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663087/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663087/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663087/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-20","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many (a) EU and (b) non-EU nationals are employed by his Department.","false","Biography information for Mr Pat McFadden","Wolverhampton South East","Mr Pat McFadden","58471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663088","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union does not hold this data. All Civil Service Departments are bound by Civil Service Nationality rules and security clearance requirements. There is no requirement for Civil Service Departments to retain this information beyond the point at which it has served its purpose.</p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-01-13T12:49:14.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663088/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663088/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663088/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-20","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many (a) EU nationals and (b) non-EU nationals are employed by his Department.","false","Biography information for Mr Pat McFadden","Wolverhampton South East","Mr Pat McFadden","58470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663089","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-16","<p>We have been clear that we want to create an environment in which the UK as a whole can continue to be a world leader in research, science and the tertiary education sector more broadly.</p><p><br>We are not going to provide a running commentary on every twist and turn of the negotiations, but we will work hard to get the best deal for Britain and its universities.<br><br></p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-01-16T11:42:30.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663089/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663089/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663089/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-20","Educational Institutions: Conferences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on further and higher education institutions' revenue from the hosting of EU conferences by such institutions.","false","Biography information for John McNally","Falkirk","John Mc Nally","58627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663090","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-13","<p>I can confirm that the Department for Exiting the European Union currently does not have the facility to allow staff to join a credit union through payroll deductions. Staff can still make arrangements to contribute to a credit union via direct debit.</p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-01-13T12:45:36.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663090/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663090/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663090/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-20","Department for Exiting the European Union: Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether his Department permits its employees to join a credit union through payroll deductions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","58451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669680","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-09","<p>Automatic enrolment will give around 11 million people the opportunity to save into a workplace pension. We expect around 10 million people to be newly saving or saving more by 2018. Figures released on 13 December by the Pensions Regulator show that over 7 million people have now been automatically enrolled by more than 341,000 employers.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-01-09T16:45:51.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669680/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669680/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669680/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent estimate his Department has made of the number of people saving into a pension scheme as a result of auto-enrolment.","false","Biography information for Nigel Mills","Amber Valley","Nigel Mills","908074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669681","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-09","<p>Automatic enrolment will give around 11 million people the opportunity to save into a workplace pension. We expect around 10 million people to be newly saving or saving more by 2018. Figures released on 13 December by the Pensions Regulator show that over 7 million people have now been automatically enrolled by more than 341,000 employers.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-01-09T16:40:42.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669681/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669681/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669681/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent estimate his Department has made of the number of people saving into a pension scheme as a result of auto-enrolment.","false","Biography information for Matt Warman","Boston and Skegness","Matt Warman","908072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669682","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-09","<p>This policy will ensure young people in the benefit system face the same choices as young people who are in work but may not be able to afford to leave home.</p><p>By encouraging young people to stay in the family home, this policy will improve work incentives and, under the Youth Obligation, more young adults will move into work, improving their living standards.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","908070","2017-01-09T16:50:52.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669682/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669682/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Housing Benefit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of his Department's policy to remove housing benefit from 18 to 21 year olds on their living standards.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","908073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669683","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-09","<p>The number of women in employment has increased by 229,000 over the past year. The female employment rate, at 69.8%, is at a record high.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-09T16:33:09.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669683/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669683/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669683/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Employment: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the recent trends in the number of women in employment.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","908071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669684","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-09","<p>This policy will ensure young people in the benefit system face the same choices as young people who are in work but may not be able to afford to leave home.</p><p>By encouraging young people to stay in the family home, this policy will improve work incentives and, under the Youth Obligation, more young adults will move into work, improving their living standards.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","908073","2017-01-09T16:50:52.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669684/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669684/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","Housing Benefit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of his Department's policy to remove housing benefit from 18 to 21 year olds on their living standards.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","908070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669685","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government has been clear that the introduction of further transitional arrangements cannot be justified, given the imperative to focus public resources on helping those who are most in need.</p><p> </p><p>There are no plans to go beyond the £1.1 billion concession introduced when Parliament considered the changes.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-01-09T16:38:52.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669685/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669685/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669685/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on improving pension transition arrangements for women born in the 1950s.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","908079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670420","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>Poland and the UK are close allies. As the Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Mrs May) said during November’s UK-Poland intergovernmental consultations: “The relationship between Poland and the United Kingdom is important both for the prosperity and the security of our countries. And as the UK leaves the EU, I am determined to strengthen this partnership”.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-01-10T15:54:24.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670420/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670420/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670420/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-20","Poland: Diplomatic Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the strength of diplomatic relations between Poland and the UK.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","908050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670421","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>On 15th December 2016, I welcomed the news that Libyan forces aligned to the Government of National Accord (GNA) defeated Daesh forces in Sirte – Daesh’s most important base outside Syria and Iraq. Although the situation remains fragile, we continue to work with the GNA to help them tackle the threat posed by extremist groups.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-10T15:14:59.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670421/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670421/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670421/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-20","Libya: Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what progress has been made on tackling Daesh in Libya.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","908047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670422","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>I arrived back from the US on January 10th 2017, where I held a series of meetings with key figures from the incoming Administration. It was clear from my discussions that the new Administration is looking forward to working closely with us to tackle the shared challenges we face. Our ambassador and Embassy in Washington are already engaging the transition team across a range of these issues. The Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Mrs May) has also spoken to President-elect Trump twice since his election, and is looking forward to visiting soon after the inauguration. The Government works regularly with the US on a range of climate and energy issues and will continue to do so.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-01-10T15:47:34.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670422/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670422/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670422/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-20","USA: Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions the Government has had with the incoming US administration on climate change.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","908045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670423","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>The Government supports the Marshall Scholarship Programme as a key element in the special relationship between the US and the UK.</p><p>We have made additional funding available to enable 40 scholars to study at UK universities from September 2017.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-01-10T16:05:05.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670423/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670423/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670423/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-20","Marshall Scholarships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what his future plans are for the Marshall Scholarship scheme.","false","Biography information for Alan Mak","Havant","Mr Alan Mak","908054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670424","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>We regularly receive reports of Daesh attacks on Christian and other religious minorities. We are working with partners to bring Daesh to justice. This includes working with the Government of Iraq to bring a proposal before the UN to gather and preserve evidence in Iraq as a first step.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-10T15:13:35.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670424/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670424/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670424/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-20","Islamic State: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports he has received on the persecution of Christian and other religious minorities by Daesh.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","908046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670425","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>I strongly condemn Sunday’s terrorist attack in Jerusalem which killed four Israeli soldiers. I understand the deep frustration on all sides at the lack of progress on the Middle East peace process but there can be absolutely no justification for terrorism.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-10T15:17:03.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670425/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670425/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670425/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-20","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of (a) trends in the level and (b) the causes of recent violence in Israel and the West Bank.","false","Biography information for Craig Tracey","North Warwickshire","Craig Tracey","908051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670426","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>A free and fair media is a fundamental building block for any functioning democracy, and for stability and prosperity worldwide. That understanding is integral to the UK’s international engagement, backed up by practical assistance, including through the FCO’s Magna Carta Fund, which is supporting relevant projects worth £1.3 million this year.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-01-10T15:37:48.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670426/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670426/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/670426/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-20","Press Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to promote press freedom abroad.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","908048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671383","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-11","<p>UK was at the forefront of negotiating the Sustainable Development Goals and we will be at the forefront of delivering them. The Goals are at the centre of all DFID’s work. The Government will be publishing a report soon that sets out the UK’s approach to delivering the Goals both domestically and internationally.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-11T17:27:40.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671383/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671383/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671383/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Developing Countries: Sustainable Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent steps she has taken to support the implementation of the Sustainable Development Goals.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","908011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671384","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-11","<p>The 2016 Multilateral Development Review demands that agencies meet international aid transparency standards and pass the same expectation to their partners. We are challenging multilaterals to publish all spending over £500, and we are expanding payment by results approaches and performance agreements, to introduce greater financial accountability. These measures will deliver increased value for money for UK taxpayers and better outcomes for the world’s poorest people.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-11T13:44:52.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671384/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671384/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671384/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","International Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans her Department has to introduce greater financial accountability to the international aid system.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","908009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671385","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-11","<p>Figures for financial year 2015/16 show that DFID spends approximately 13% of its budget through contractors. The House will know that I have recently instructed my officials to undertake a review of how we work with our suppliers. It is essential that all of DFID’s contractors and partners are fully open and transparent, uphold the highest standards and are held to account for those standards.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2017-01-11T14:45:36.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671385/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671385/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/671385/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Department for International Development: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much her Department has spent on private consultancies in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","908003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661592","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>The information was not available in time to publish in the 2015-16 Annual Report and Accounts, but expenses data for the Anti-Corruption Champion, including all 2015-16 data, will be published in the Cabinet Office Quarterly Transparency Return in March and made available on <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a>.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-01-12T09:08:56.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661592/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661592/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661592/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-19","Anti-corruption Champion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 19 April 2016 to Question 33684, on what page in the Cabinet Office annual report and accounts 2015-16 the specific costs incurred by the Government's Anti-Corruption Champion are set out.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","58106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661593","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government Transformation Strategy will be published in due course.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-01-09T11:43:41.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661593/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661593/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661593/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-19","Government Departments: Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether he plans to publish the Government Transformation Strategy before 1 January 2017.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","58341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661594","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-01-09T16:06:04.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661594/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661594/answer","UKSA response to PQ58343 v.02.pdf","UKSA Response to PQ58343","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661594/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-19","Low Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the number of people in (a) Scotland and (b) the UK (i) between the ages of 16 and 21 earing less than £8.45 per hour, (ii) aged under 18 earning £4 per hour, (iii) aged 21 and over earning £6.95 per hour, (iv) aged 18 to 20 earning £5.55 per hour and (v) who are apprentices and earing £3.40 per hour.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","58343"
