"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661597","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-11","<p>HM Treasury has two board level diversity champions, (i) Treasury’s Chief Economic Adviser and (ii) Treasury’s Director of Personal Tax, Welfare and Pensions Group.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-01-11T10:30:35.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661597/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661597/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661597/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-19","Treasury: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, who the diversity champion is on his departmental board.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","58244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661598","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-09","<p>Business rates are based on valuations from the Valuation Office Agency and we do not intervene in their independent assessments. We have put in place a £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme for England to support ratepayers at the 2017 revaluation.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-09T17:46:35.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661598/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661598/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661598/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-19","Non-domestic Rates: Financial Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure that proposed increases in business rates do not have a negative effect on the financial services sector.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","58221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661599","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government continues to undertake a range of analyses to inform the UK’s position for the upcoming EU exit negotiations. We are seeking the best possible arrangement for the United Kingdom and the work being conducted reflects this.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-01-09T14:52:11.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661599/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661599/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661599/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-19","Public Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to publish an estimate of the potential effect on the public finances of the UK's decision to leave the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","58259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661600","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) publish forecasts for the employment rate for all those aged over 16. This differs from the main Office for National Statistics measure which looks at those aged between 16 and 64.</p><p> </p><p>In the November 2016 <em>Economic and Fiscal Outlook,</em> the OBR projected the 16+ employment rate to stand at the highest annual rate since 1974 in 2016, at 60.5%, before falling to 60.1% in 2018, 59.9% in 2020 and 59.7% by 2022Q1.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-01-13T11:55:34.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661600/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661600/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661600/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-19","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the potential for further increases in the employment rate in the UK economy over the next (a) two, (b) four and (c) six years.","false","Biography information for John Penrose","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","58255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661601","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-09","<p>The expected yield for the apprenticeship levy is published in table C.5: ‘Current Receipts’, in the Autumn Statement 2016 document available here: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/571559/autumn_statement_2016_web.pdf</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-01-09T14:13:39.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661601/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661601/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661601/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-19","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the revenue to be raised from the Apprenticeship Levy in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19 and (c) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","58108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661602","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Vehicle Excise Duty (VED) liability for any particular vehicle is set in accordance with its certificate of conformity at the time of first registration, and consequently consumers are paying VED correctly.</p><p> </p><p>Any revisions to the software used in the affected models are being assessed by the relevant European approval authorities. This comprises a series of checks, including that the CO2 emissions remain the same or better.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-01-09T13:53:51.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661602/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661602/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661602/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-19","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 2 November 2016 to Question 13949, if he will publish the Government's analysis on determining any loss of VED revenues following VW Group's use of defeat devices; and whether any of the models among the 1.2 million vehicles affected were subsequently re-banded.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","58110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661603","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Government is committed to increasing competition in banking and creating an environment in which firms compete to offer a range of products that suit the varying needs of their customers. Both existing and prospective mortgage borrowers may benefit from shopping around to find the best deal available to them.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has not undertaken a formal assessment of the effects that the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) Rules on mortgage affordability assessments have had on the ability of borrowers to switch providers.</p><p> </p><p>Although the Treasury sets the legal framework for the regulation of financial services, specific rules are a matter for the FCA whose day-to-day operations are independent from government control and influence.</p><p> </p><p>In May 2016 the FCA published a review which assessed the impact of recent changes to the regulation of mortgage lending. Where lending is affordable, the FCA did not see evidence that the responsible lending rules have prevented creditworthy consumers obtaining loans.</p><p> </p><p>The full review can be found here: https://www.fca.org.uk/publication/thematic-reviews/tr16-04.pdf</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","58151","2017-01-11T10:35:45.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661603/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661603/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661603/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-19","Mortgages","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment the Government has made of the effect of Financial Conduct Authority requirements for mortgage affordability assessments on the ability of home owners to re-mortgage or switch mortgage provider.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","58150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661604","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Government is committed to increasing competition in banking and creating an environment in which firms compete to offer a range of products that suit the varying needs of their customers. Both existing and prospective mortgage borrowers may benefit from shopping around to find the best deal available to them.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has not undertaken a formal assessment of the effects that the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) Rules on mortgage affordability assessments have had on the ability of borrowers to switch providers.</p><p> </p><p>Although the Treasury sets the legal framework for the regulation of financial services, specific rules are a matter for the FCA whose day-to-day operations are independent from government control and influence.</p><p> </p><p>In May 2016 the FCA published a review which assessed the impact of recent changes to the regulation of mortgage lending. Where lending is affordable, the FCA did not see evidence that the responsible lending rules have prevented creditworthy consumers obtaining loans.</p><p> </p><p>The full review can be found here: https://www.fca.org.uk/publication/thematic-reviews/tr16-04.pdf</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","58150","2017-01-11T10:35:45.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661604/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661604/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661604/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-19","Mortgages","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps the Government is taking to assist home owners who seek to re-mortgage but who, following the Mortgage Market Review, no longer meet Financial Conduct Authority requirements on mortgage affordability assessments.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","58151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661605","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-09","<p>Christine Hewitt, Director, People, Capability and Change is the Board Diversity Champion in the Department for Communities and Local Government. We also have senior Diversity Champions for BAME, Race, Disability, Women, LGBT and Social Mobility as well as our Departmental Diversity Champion who work closely with our Networks in embedding Diversity and Inclusion messages and in promoting opportunities. Our Permanent Secretary is the Gender Champion for the Civil Service and all of our Champions and Networks are aligned with Civil Service governance, Networks and wider communities.</p><p>The Government takes its commitments to Diversity and Inclusion very seriously, and as a result the action in the Talent Action Plan 2015 has been completed and is referenced in the 2016 Talent Action Plan “progress to date” section. All departments, including new departments Department for Exiting the European Union (DExEU) and Department for International Trade (DIT) have nominated overall diversity champions. They are responsible for providing an overall insight for all protected characteristics.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-09T16:23:53.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661605/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661605/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661605/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-19","Department for Communities and Local Government: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, who the diversity champion is on his departmental board.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","58230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661607","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government has published Core Spending Power tables measuring the core revenue funding available for local authority services in each year of this Parliament, available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/core-spending-power-provisional-local-government-finance-settlement-2017-to-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/core-spending-power-provisional-local-government-finance-settlement-2017-to-2018</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-09T16:49:00.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661607/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661607/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661607/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-19","Local Government Finance: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate his Department has made of the potential effect on the budget of each local authority in Greater Manchester of the (a) reduction in the New Homes Bonus scheme and (b) additional funding through the adult social care support grant in each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","58291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661608","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Department does not hold the specific information requested. The Secretary of State’s role in a compulsory purchase order ends when he issues a decision whether or not to confirm the order. We have no role in the amount of compensation paid.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-02-27T18:00:44.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661608/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661608/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661608/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-19","Compulsory Purchase: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the cost to the public purse has been of compulsory purchase orders in each London borough in each year since 1990.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","58195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661609","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Department does not hold the specific information requested, compulsory purchase order data only exists from 2011 to present day. However, to obtain this information would involve interrogating individual case records, at disproportionate cost. We do not hold information on compulsory purchase orders for heritage purposes which are the responsibility of the Department for Culture, Media and Sport.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-09T16:19:41.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661609/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661609/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661609/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-19","Compulsory Purchase: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many compulsory purchase orders have been made, by London borough, (a) in total, (b) for heritage purposes and (c) to provide housing in each year since 1990.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","58193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661611","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Department does not hold the specific information requested, compulsory purchase orders data only exists from 2011 to present day. However, to obtain this information would involve interrogating individual case records, at disproportionate cost.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-09T16:19:00.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661611/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661611/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661611/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-19","Compulsory Purchase","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which local authorities have made compulsory purchase orders in each year since 1990.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","58194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661612","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-09","<p>From April 2016 applications for prior approval are required to note how many homes will be permitted. There is no requirement to note how much office space is to change to residential use. The net additional dwellings data shows that the right has made a valuable contribution to housing supply, delivering over 12,800 homes in the year to March 2016.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-09T16:36:52.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661612/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661612/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661612/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-19","Offices: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect on the amount of office floor space in London of the relaxation of permitted development rights.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","58273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661613","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Adult Social Care Support Grant is a one-off grant to councils in recognition of the particular pressures on adult social care services in 2017-18, and will be allocated to councils based on relative need using the Department of Health's social care Relative Needs Formula.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-09T16:28:05.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661613/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661613/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661613/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-19","Social Services: Council Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to his oral contribution of 15 December 2016, Official Report, columns 976 to 979, on the local government finance settlement, whether the decision by a local authority to raise revenue through the adult social care precept was a criterion used by his Department in assessing the allocation of adult social care support grant awards.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","58326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661614","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-01","<p>For the financial year 2016-17, the Government allowed local authorities with adult social care responsibilities to increase their council tax by 2% to help fund adult social care (the ‘Adult Social Care Precept’), in addition to the permitted 2% ‘core’ increase. Salford City Council set a 3.75% increase in 2016-17, of which 2% was for the Adult Social Care Precept. Please see: <br> <br> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/council-tax-levels-set-by-local-authorities-in-england-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/council-tax-levels-set-by-local-authorities-in-england-2016-to-2017</a>.</p><p>Under new proposals announced as part of the provisional Local Government Finance Settlement on 15 December 2016, the Adult Social Care Precept for 2017-18 will be worth up to an additional 3%. Assuming that local authorities make full use of the 3% flexibility, the Adult Social Care Precept could generate more than £1 billion in total in 2017-18, and £4.4 million for Salford City Council. <br> <br> The attached table shows the potential total of Adult Social Care Precept receipts in 2017-18, assuming that local authorities make full use of the 3% flexibility. Whether or not they wish to do so would be a matter for each council.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","58333 ; 58334","2017-02-01T15:04:33.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661614/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661614/answer","UIN58325adultsocialcareprecepttable.doc","UIN58325 Adult Social Care Precept table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661614/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661614/answer/previousversion/29817","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-19","Social Services: Council Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the amount that each local authority could raise if they employed use of the three per cent social care precept on council tax in the 2016-17 financial year.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","58325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661615","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-09","<p>Information on the total amount of current and capital expenditure on services by organisation in Yorkshire and the Humber is publically available on gov.uk as part of the Country and Regional Analysis statistical release. This information covers 2011-12 through to 2015-16 and can be found at the following web link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/country-and-regional-analysis-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/country-and-regional-analysis-2016</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-09T17:03:31.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661615/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661615/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661615/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-19","Department for Communities and Local Government: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the value of (a) staffing expenditure, (b) other revenue costs and (c) capital expenditure by his Department and its arms-length bodies in whole or in part in Yorkshire and the Humber in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","58317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661616","Department of Health","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government does not collect information on local authority expenditure on their role in relation to the Deprivation of Liberty Safeguards.</p><p> </p><p>The Department published an impact assessment on the Deprivation of Liberty Safeguards in 2008.</p><p> </p><p>Official statistics on the Deprivation of Liberty Safeguards are published annually by NHS Digital. Information on the number of applications to each local authority and the outcome of those applications is available at:</p><p> </p><p>- 2014/15 - <a href="http://content.digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB18577/dols-eng-1415-ann-a.xlsx" target="_blank">http://content.digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB18577/dols-eng-1415-ann-a.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p>- 2015/16 - <a href="http://content.digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB21814/dols-eng-1516-annx-c.xlsx" target="_blank">http://content.digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB21814/dols-eng-1516-annx-c.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p>Data relating to 2016/17 will be published by NHS Digital in autumn 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Additional funding was provided to local authorities for their role in relation to the Deprivation of Liberty Safeguards in 2015 and was allocated using the Relative Needs Formula. The amount provided to each local authority is provided in the attached table.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","58331 ; 58332 ; 58347","2017-01-09T16:29:08.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661616/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661616/answer","PQ58437 Gareth Thomas additional table - DoLS funding per LA.docx","PQ58437 Gareth Thomas additional table - DoLS fund","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661616/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Mental Capacity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much has been spent by each local authority on Deprivation of Liberty Safegu