"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661622","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-09","<p>The 2017-18 Adult Social Care Support Grant that was announced alongside the provisional local government finance settlement and will be allocated according to the Adult Social Care Relative Needs Formula.</p><p>The distribution of this grant for each council with adult social care responsibilities is set out in the Core Spending Power supporting tables published as part of the department's announcement of the provisional local government finance settlement. These tables are available on the department's website and can be accessed via the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/577770/Core_Spending_Power_Supporting_Information.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/577770/Core_Spending_Power_Supporting_Information.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-09T17:10:05.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661622/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661622/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661622/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-19","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to his oral contribution of 15 December 2016, Official Report, columns 976-9, on the local government finance settlement, what methodology his Department plans to use to determine relative need when awarding the adult social care support grant in 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","58335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661623","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government has published Core Spending Power tables measuring the core revenue funding available for local authority services in each year of this Parliament, available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/core-spending-power-provisional-local-government-finance-settlement-2017-to-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/core-spending-power-provisional-local-government-finance-settlement-2017-to-2018</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-09T17:08:30.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661623/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661623/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661623/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-19","Local Government Finance: Salford","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the provisional local government finance settlement 2017 to 2018, by how much Salford City Council's new homes bonus payments will be reduced; how much Salford City Council will receive from the adult social care support grant; and what the net effect is of those funding changes.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","58336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661624","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-09","<p>There are no legal powers to compel an occupier to notify TV licensing that no TV licence is required. All TV Licensing letters ask people who don’t need a licence to get in touch in order to update their records.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-01-09T14:14:15.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661624/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661624/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661624/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-19","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what legal powers TV Licensing have to compel an occupier who does not have television receiving equipment to notify TV Licensing that no television licence is required.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","58337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661625","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-09","<p>We have received one representation about the tone of letters sent by TV Licensing to an occupier who did ​not have television receiving equipment but who chose not to notify TV Licensing of that fact.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-01-09T14:15:37.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661625/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661625/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661625/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-19","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether she has received any representations about the tone of letters sent by TV Licensing to occupiers who do not have television receiving equipment but who choose not to notify TV Licensing of that fact.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","58338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661626","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>In delivering the Emergency Services Network (ESN), the mobile network operator EE will deliver up to 291 new mast sites. Government will deliver approximately 230 further sites (known as the “Extended Area Services” (EAS) sites) in the most remote and rural areas of Great Britain.</p><p>EE has indicated that for the sites they are building for ESN, they will provide detailed information to the mobile network operators on the locations once sites for new masts are legally acquired and planning permission has been granted.</p><p>For EAS sites, proposed locations have been shared with the Scottish and Welsh Governments. Planning applications due to be submitted during 2017 will confirm and make public the precise locations of these sites.</p><p>There are currently no new sites proposed in the constituency of Salisbury as part of ESN.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","58327","2017-01-09T13:50:51.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661626/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661626/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661626/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-19","Aerials: Salisbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many mobile telephone masts are planned to be built in Salisbury constituency under the Emergency Services Network Mobile Services contract.","false","Biography information for John Glen","Salisbury","John Glen","58328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661627","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>In delivering the Emergency Services Network (ESN), the mobile network operator EE will deliver up to 291 new mast sites. Government will deliver approximately 230 further sites (known as the “Extended Area Services” (EAS) sites) in the most remote and rural areas of Great Britain.</p><p>EE has indicated that for the sites they are building for ESN, they will provide detailed information to the mobile network operators on the locations once sites for new masts are legally acquired and planning permission has been granted.</p><p>For EAS sites, proposed locations have been shared with the Scottish and Welsh Governments. Planning applications due to be submitted during 2017 will confirm and make public the precise locations of these sites.</p><p>There are currently no new sites proposed in the constituency of Salisbury as part of ESN.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","58328","2017-01-09T13:50:51.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661627/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661627/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661627/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-19","Emergency Services Network: Aerials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether data held by her Department on the geographic location of mobile telephone masts constructed under the Emergency Services Network Mobile Services contract will be released.","false","Biography information for John Glen","Salisbury","John Glen","58327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661628","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-12","<p>The Department can confirm following a detailed search of its internal record systems that iNHouse Communications Ltd are not a registered supplier and consequently there are no records of any commercial contracts being awarded during the past five years.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-01-12T17:43:26.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661628/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661628/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661628/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-19","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: iNHouse Communications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether her Department is in communication with iNHouse Communications Ltd in relation to any ongoing commercial tender process.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","58312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661629","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-12","<p>The Department for Culture, Media &amp; Sport has not awarded any commercial contracts to iNHouse Communications Ltd in the last five years.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-01-12T17:44:15.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661629/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661629/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661629/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-19","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: iNHouse Communications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether her Department has awarded any commercial contracts to iNHouse Communications Ltd in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","58313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661630","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-13","<p>Improving mobile connectivity across the UK is a priority for the Government. Roaming was considered in 2014 and rejected as it risked discouraging investment and increasing complete not spots. The Government instead favoured legally binding licence obligations on each MNO to provide voice/SMS text coverage to at least 90% of the UK’s landmass by end-2017. The licence obligations arising from the December 2014 agreement have locked in investment of £5 billion and are delivering improved coverage across the UK. Ofcom's 2016 Connected Nations Report shows that 99% of UK premises now have indoor voice coverage and 96% have indoor 4G data coverage. Our recent reforms to mobile planning laws and proposed reforms of the Electronic Communications Code, will support further investment and improvements in connectivity across the UK and reduce not spots.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-01-13T13:30:14.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661630/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661630/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661630/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-19","Mobile Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if her Department will undertake an impact assessment of macro not-spot roaming in order to improve mobile coverage.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","58264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661631","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Government recognises the importance of people having connectivity where they live, work and travel and is taking firm action to improve this right across the UK.</p><p>The legally binding agreement that we reached with industry in 2014 locked in over £5bn of investment in mobile infrastructure and will result in nearly at least 90% voice/SMS text coverage of the UK’s landmass by the end of 2017</p><p>But we agree with NIC that there is still further to go. We want the UK to become a world leader in 5G, which is why we announced over £1bn of funding at the Autumn Statement to support the deployment of the next generation of digital infrastructure, including an ambitious programme of 5G testbeds.</p><p>We will consider the NIC's recommendations carefully.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-01-13T13:30:59.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661631/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661631/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661631/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-19","5G","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the report of the National Infrastructure Commission, entitled Connected Future, published on 14 December 2016, what her Department's plans are for preparing the UK's mobile telephone infrastructure for universal geographical coverage of 5G.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","58265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661632","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-10","<p>Sue Owen, The Permanent Secretary at DCMS is the lead Civil Service Diversity Champion, and for the department.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-01-10T14:31:57.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661632/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661632/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661632/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-19","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, who the diversity champion is on her departmental board.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","58231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661633","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-10","<p>We have made no assessment of the potential merits of a portable television licence for people living in multiple accommodation.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-01-10T14:51:54.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661633/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661633/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661633/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-19","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of portable television licences for people living in multiple accommodation.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","58171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661634","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-09","<p>We will consider this in light of Ofcom’s analysis on this issue which was included in the broadband Universal Service Obligation report published on 16 December.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-01-09T12:36:49.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661634/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661634/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661634/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-19","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of providing social tariffs to improve access to broadband among low-income households.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","58093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661635","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-09","<p>We will carefully consider Ofcom’s broadband USO analysis, published on 16 December, before reaching any decision on the design of the broadband USO, including the minimum speed and any other quality criteria that might apply.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-01-09T12:35:26.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661635/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661635/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661635/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-19","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if she will undertake a further review of the adequacy of a 10 Mbit/s broadband speed before deciding on the level at which such a speed should be set in a Universal Service Obligation.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","58204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661636","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Permanent Secretary, Stephen Lovegrove, is the Ministry of Defence's Diversity and Inclusion champion, and acts as an advocate for diversity and inclusion issues on the Defence Board.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-01-09T16:08:11.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661636/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661636/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661636/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-19","Ministry of Defence: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, who the diversity champion is on his departmental board.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","58232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661637","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-10","<p>Terrorist organisations such as AQ and Daesh prosper in ungoverned environments where they have the freedom to develop their capabilities. This remains a particular concern in Yemen where AQAP are benefitting from the continued instability that results from Houthi aggression.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2017-01-10T16:05:50.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661637/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661637/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661637/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-19","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to his comments on the Andrew Marr BBC TV programme on 11 December 2016, on Yemen, what the evidential basis is for his statement that Houthis in Yemen are supported by al-Qaeda.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","58289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661638","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-10","<p>The Ministry of Defence has not yet confirmed which ammunition it might use for the F-35B Lightning gun.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-01-10T16:07:37.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661638/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661638/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661638/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-19","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what ammunition his Department plans to use for the Semi-Armour-Piercing High-Explosive Incendiary-Tracer round for the F35B Lightning II gun.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","58279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661639","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-10","<p>Flight sciences testing is intended to expand the operational envelope of the F-35 incrementally and safely. As at September 2016, 74.5% of F-35B Lightning flight sciences test points had been completed for the year. This was ahead of schedule.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-01-10T16:11:19.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661639/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661639/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661639/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-19","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 16 December 2016 to Question 57051, what the final test point score was for the F-35B Lightning II; and what the planned such test point score was in flight sciences testing through to 30 September 2016.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","58280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661640","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-10","<p>Of those Armed Forces personnel and Ministry of Defence civilian staff who attended the naming ceremony for Royal Fleet Auxiliary Tiderace in December 2016, only the Chief of Materiel (Fleet) and his Military Assistant travelled to the Republic of Korea (ROK) specifically for the event.</p><p> </p><p>Costs of accommodation and transfers within the ROK were funded under the contract with Daewoo Shipbuilding and Marine Engineering.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","58281","2017-01-10T16:14:14.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661640/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661640/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661640/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-19","RFA Tiderace","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 15 December 2016 to Question 56630, what the cost was to the public purse of (a) travel and (b) accommodation for the 25 members of the Armed Forces and 10 MoD civilian staff who attended the naming ceremony for RFA Tiderace.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","58282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661642","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-10","<p>Of those Armed Forces personnel and Ministry of Defence civilian staff who attended the naming ceremony for Royal Fleet Auxiliary Tiderace in December 2016, only the Chief of Materiel (Fleet) and his Military Assistant travelled to the Republic of Korea (ROK) specifically for the event.</p><p> </p><p>Costs of accommodation and transfers within the ROK were funded under the contract with Daewoo Shipbuilding and Marine Engineering.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","58282","2017-01-10T16:14:14.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661642/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661642/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661642/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-19","RFA Tiderace","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 19 December 2016 to Question 57254, what the cost was to the public purse of accommodation in South Korea for the Lady Sponsor for the naming ceremony for RFA Tiderace.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","58281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661643","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-11","<p>As a result of both the merger of Headquarters of 15 (North East) Brigade with 4 Mechanised Brigade and the move of Headquarters 1st (UK) Division from Germany to York there were no civil servant redundancies and no external recruitment. Civil servants were relocated from Germany to the UK and vacancies were filled by existing civil servants. Gratuity payments made to locally employed staff in Germany are considered to be a part of the wider drawdown of UK forces from Germany and are therefore not included.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-01-11T16:21:49.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661643/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661643/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661643/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-19","Imphal Barracks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the cost to the public purse was of (a) recruitment and (b) redundancy as a result of the rebasing programme at Imphal Barracks.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","58298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661644","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-11","<p>The costs of relocating military units from Imphal Barracks, York to Catterick form part of the routine military rotations and cannot be apportioned to individual moves. The accommodation at Catterick was not upgraded as a result of this move.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-01-11T16:20:08.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661644/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661644/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661644/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-19","Military Bases: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the total cost to the public purse was of locating Army units from Imphal Barracks in York to Catterick Barracks in 2014; and what proportion of that cost was spent on upgrading accommodation in Catterick.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","58299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661645","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-10","<p>Work has recently started on the refurbishment of Imphal Barracks in order to accommodate 1st Division Headquarters. Work is ongoing and final costs will not be available until Financial Year 2017-18.</p><p>While there is no Defence requirement for Imphal Barracks after 2031, the necessary refurbishment works represent value for money to avoid any costly repairs and to ensure the site remains safe and compliant for the occupants over the next 15 years.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-01-10T16:15:54.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661645/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661645/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661645/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-19","Imphal Barracks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the cost to the public purse was of refurbishing Imphal Barracks in York in order to accommodate 1st Division Headquarters.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","58300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661646","Department of Health","false","2017-01-09","<p>In England veterans are able to access high quality clinically appropriate prosthetic limbs from the National Health Service either through local disablement services, or through one of the nine centres that have been selected to provide enhanced services for veterans. The veterans’ prosthetic panel continues to support these veterans, ensuring they receive the latest specification prosthetics. Health is a devolved issue however if a service is provided by the Ministry of Defence it will be available to all veterans across the United Kingdom and veterans with complex needs can be referred to the new Veterans Complex Prosthetic Assessment Clinic provided by the Ministry of Defence at Headley Court.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-09T16:22:00.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661646/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661646/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661646/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Veterans: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what support his Department provides to veterans who have lost one or more limb during their service.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","58227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661647","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-09","<p>When the Saudi-led coalition concluded its investigations.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2017-01-09T16:06:16.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661647/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661647/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661647/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-19","Yemen: Cluster Munitions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he was first made aware of the results of the internal investigation that found recent use of UK cluster munitions in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","58304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661648","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-10","<p>The Ascension Island Runway Resurfacing Project is a United States Air Force (USAF) led project and will be co-ordinated in consultation with the Ascension Island Government Conservation Department. The design and scope assessment has been contracted-out by the USAF and we are assured that all environmental considerations will be factored into this assessment. The Ministry of Defence has also provided the contractor with additional information for the environmental assessment and will continue to liaise with all stakeholders as the project develops.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-01-10T16:13:19.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661648/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661648/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661648/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-19","Ascension Island: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what environmental impact assessment his Department plans to undertake for the runway resurfacing project on Ascension Island; and whether that assessment will be open to stakeholder consultation.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","58274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661649","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-12","<p>UK Armed Forces personnel have had no involvement intraining Saudi armed forces in the use of cluster munitions since the UK signed the Convention on Cluster Munitions in 2008.</p><p>The UK has provided training courses for Royal Saudi Air Force personnel and artillery training for the Royal Saudi Land Forces.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","58373","2017-01-12T16:09:06.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661649/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661649/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661649/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-19","Saudi Arabia: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what involvement UK armed forces personnel have had in training Saudi armed forces in (a) cluster bomb use, (b) air warfare skills and (c) artillery techniques.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","58305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661650","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-09","<p>I regularly discuss a range of defence and security issues with my Saudi counterparts, including the use of cluster munitions.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2017-01-09T16:06:46.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661650/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661650/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661650/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-19","Yemen: Cluster Munitions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he discussed with his Saudi counterpart its recent use of cluster munitions in Yemen in the last six months; and what the outcome of each of those discussions was.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","58303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661651","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government has taken action across a range of areas – skills, research, infrastructure and facilities, knowledge exchange, access to finance, intellectual property and tax incentives - to ensure the strong development of university-business collaboration and the application of research to support sustainable economic growth.</p><p>At the Autumn Statement, the Government committed an extra £2 billion a year in research and development by 2020- 21, including for the Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund. The Chancellor confirmed a further £100m support for collaboration between universities across the range of knowledge exchange activity and a further £100m for Innovate UK for the Biomedical Catalyst.</p><p>The creation of UK Research &amp; Innovation - bringing together the Research Councils, Innovate UK and the research and knowledge exchange functions of the Higher Education Funding Council for England is an opportunity to take a strategic approach and to simplify funding arrangements for research, innovation and commercialisation.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-01-09T11:15:06.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661651/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661651/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661651/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-19","Universities: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to help facilitate collaboration between universities and the private sector.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","58322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661652","Department for Education","false","2017-01-27","<p>The department does not hold the information centrally in the form requested. Expenditure is not categorised by region and this could be obtained only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-27T14:04:03.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661652/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661652/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661652/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Department for Education: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the value of (a) staffing expenditure, (b) other revenue costs and (c) capital expenditure by her Department and its arms-length bodies in whole or in part in Yorkshire and the Humber in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","58318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661653","Department for Education","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Higher Education Council for Funding in England (HEFCE) reports that the higher education sector was in sound financial health in 2014/15. In the same academic year, overseas fee income accounted for nearly 13% of total sector income on average.</p><p>International students make an important economic and cultural contribution to the UK. The UK has, and will continue to have, a world class education system that attracts students from across the world.</p><p>The latest report, entitled ‘Financial Health of the higher education sector: 2015-16 to 2018-19 forecasts’ can be found on HEFCE’s website at:</p><p><a href="http://www.hefce.ac.uk/media/HEFCE,2014/Content/Pubs/2016/201634/HEFCE2016_34.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.hefce.ac.uk/media/HEFCE,2014/Content/Pubs/2016/201634/HEFCE2016_34.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-01-09T10:03:23.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661653/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661653/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661653/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the potential impact of falling international student numbers on the financial sustainability of the UK university sector.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","58320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661654","Department for Education","false","2017-01-09","<p>The apprenticeship levy will raise £2.8 billion a year across the UK by 2020</p><p>Through the levy, we will be investing £2.5 billion a year in England on apprenticeships by 2020</p><p>The table below provides the latest provisional figures for apprenticeships budgets (excluding non-participation budgets, Apprenticeship Grant for Employers (AGE) and Employer Ownership Pilot (EOP).</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>2018-19</p></td><td><p>2019-20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Department for Education, £m</p></td><td><p>2,010</p></td><td><p>2,231</p></td><td><p>2,450</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Funds will be available to levy payers through the digital apprenticeship service depending on their levy payment and their workforce who are resident in England.</p><p>Funding for the devolved administrations has also been announced: https://www.gov.uk/government/news/uk-government-agrees-apprenticeship-levy-funding-deal-with-devolved-administrations</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-01-09T14:08:57.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661654/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661654/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661654/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Apprentices: Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much funding will be available through the digital apprenticeship service in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19 and (c) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","58224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661655","Department for Education","false","2017-01-09","<p>The apprenticeship levy will raise £2.8 billion a year across the UK by 2020</p><p>Through the levy, we will be investing £2.5 billion a year in England on apprenticeships by 2020</p><p>The table below provides the latest provisional figures for apprenticeships budgets (excluding non-participation budgets, Apprenticeship Grant for Employers (AGE) and Employer Ownership Pilot (EOP).</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>2018-19</p></td><td><p>2019-20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Department for Education: £m</p></td><td><p>2,010</p></td><td><p>2,231</p></td><td><p>2,450</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Funds will be available to levy payers through the digital apprenticeship service depending on their levy payment and their workforce who are resident in England.</p><p>Funding for the devolved administrations has also been announced: https://www.gov.uk/government/news/uk-government-agrees-apprenticeship-levy-funding-deal-with-devolved-administrations</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-01-09T14:12:53.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661655/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661655/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661655/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much is planned to be spent on apprenticeships in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19 and (c) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","58225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661656","Department for Education","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Department does not collect information on the number of grandparents providing free childcare for working parents, however information is available on the proportion of families using grandparents for childcare.</p><p>The Department’s Childcare and Early Years Survey of Parents contains information on the proportion of families using grandparents for childcare by family type and work status. This information is published for the past five surveys online at:</p><p>2009 Survey - Table c2.2 (page 196):<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/181743/DFE-RR054.pdf</p><p>2010 Survey - Table c2.4 (page 233):<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/211819/OSR_12_2012_Updated_Jun13.pdf</p><p><br>2011 Survey - Table c2.6 (page 232):<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/211820/SFR08-2013Text97-03_Updated_Jun13.pdf</p><p>2012-13 Survey - Table c2.6 (page 271):<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/275992/SFR06-2014_Childcare_and_Early_Years_Survey_of_Parents_2012-13_final.pdf</p><p>2014-15 Survey - Table c2.6 (page 294):<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/516924/SFR09-2016_Childcare_and_Early_Years_Parents_Survey_2014-15_report.pdf.pdf</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-11T15:28:49.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661656/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661656/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661656/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Grandparents: Parental Responsibility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of recent trends in the number of grandparents providing free childcare for working parents; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","58189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661657","Department for Education","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Department does not collect specific data on the number of teachers who leave the UK to work abroad, whether they are UK nationals or overseas nationals who undertook their teacher training in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>However, at a national level we are retaining and recruiting the teachers we need, and we have more teachers in state-funded schools in England than ever before. Of the teachers who trained in the 2014/15 academic year and who have successfully completed their training, 95% were employed in a state-funded school in England within six months of qualifying.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise that given the strong graduate labour market there are challenges in recruiting and retaining teachers, particularly in certain subjects and for some specific schools. We are working hard to address the issues that cause teachers to consider leaving the profession, such as unnecessary workload and poor pupil behaviour, to ensure that teaching remains an attractive and rewarding career.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-01-11T13:46:16.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661657/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661657/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661657/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to encourage teachers to remain in the UK after they have completed their studies.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","58190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661658","Department for Education","false","2017-01-11","<p>We will invest at least £200 million in places for pupils with special educational needs and disabilities that have education, health and care plans. We will distribute this funding to local authorities in England to support them to provide new places and improve facilities in both mainstream and special schools. This is over and above the basic need funding that we allocate to local authorities to support them to provide new school places. Local authorities are also free to use basic need funding to invest in places for pupils with special needs and disabilities where they identify that to be where the need is greatest.</p><p> </p><p>We will allocate this funding to local authorities in England and we will say more about this in 2017. Education is a devolved matter, meaning that the Northern Ireland Assembly is responsible for pupil place policy in Northern Ireland.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-01-11T15:10:17.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661658/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661658/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661658/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to ensure special needs places are available for all children who have a statement of need; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","58188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661659","Department for Education","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear that tackling poverty and disadvantage, and delivering real social reform, is a priority for this Government. We are considering the future direction for children’s centres and will provide further detail in due course, including how stakeholders and members of the public can contribute.</p><p> </p><p>The requirement for Ofsted to undertake the inspections of Sure Start children’s centres is currently suspended pending the consideration of their future direction as mentioned above. The Secretary of State has not had any recent discussions with Ofsted on the inspection of children’s centres.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","58217","2017-01-09T17:20:46.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661659/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661659/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661659/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Children's Centres: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent discussions she has had with Ofsted on inspections of children's centres.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","58292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661660","Department for Education","false","2017-02-06","<p>The diversity champion on the Departmental Board is Juliet Chua.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-06T17:51:17.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661660/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661660/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661660/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Department for Education: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, who the diversity champion is on her departmental board.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","58233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661661","Department for Education","false","2017-01-11","<p>We are working through the best course of action on this issue. The Secretary of State has had no meetings to date. As the minister responsible for school food, I attended the School Food Plan Alliance meeting on 6 December. Departmental officials are meeting with the School Food Plan Alliance, School Food Matters and other stakeholders in the new year to discuss options.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","58160","2017-01-11T15:04:09.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661661/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661661/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661661/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","School Meals: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 19 December 2016 to Question 57119, what stakeholders she has met since 18 August 2016 to discuss mechanisms to ensure that academies and free schools meet the School Food Standards.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","58161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661662","Department for Education","false","2017-01-11","<p>We are working through the best course of action on this issue. The Secretary of State has had no meetings to date. As the minister responsible for school food, I attended the School Food Plan Alliance meeting on 6 December. Departmental officials are meeting with the School Food Plan Alliance, School Food Matters and other stakeholders in the new year to discuss options.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","58161","2017-01-11T15:04:09.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661662/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661662/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661662/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Free Schools: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 16 December 2016 to Question 57119, what progress she has made in ensuring that academies and free schools meet the School Food Standards since the publication of Childhood Obesity: a plan for action.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","58160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661663","Department for Education","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear that tackling poverty and disadvantage, and delivering real social reform, is a priority for this Government. We are considering the future direction for children’s centres and will provide further detail in due course, including how stakeholders and members of the public can contribute.</p><p> </p><p>The requirement for Ofsted to undertake the inspections of Sure Start children’s centres is currently suspended pending the consideration of their future direction as mentioned above. The Secretary of State has not had any recent discussions with Ofsted on the inspection of children’s centres.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","58292","2017-01-09T17:20:46.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661663/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661663/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661663/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Children's Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when the Government plans to publish its consultation on the future of children's centres.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","58217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661664","Department for Education","false","2017-01-09","<p>The most recent data held by the Department shows that from 2008 – 2013, the proportion of male staff in the early years workforce has consistently remained at 2% (Childcare Provider Survey, 2013).</p><p> </p><p>The Department will be publishing a workforce strategy in 2017, which will seek to remove the barriers to attracting, retaining and developing staff.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-09T09:56:22.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661664/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661664/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661664/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Pre-school Education: Males","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of early years' practitioners are male.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","58218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661665","Department for Education","false","2017-01-09","<p>On 20 October, the department published the early years foundation stage profile (EYFSP) results for the 2015 to 2016 academic year, at national and local authority level. The EYFSP results are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/early-years-foundation-stage-profile-results-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/early-years-foundation-stage-profile-results-2015-to-2016</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The data to determine the number and proportion of children in receipt of the early years pupil premium who achieve a good level of development and at least the expected level across all early learning goals are not readily available, and could only be compiled at disproportionate cost.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-09T17:25:11.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661665/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661665/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661665/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Pupil Premium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to early-years foundation stage profile results, what number and proportion of children in receipt of the early-years pupil premium achieved (a) a good level of development and (b) at least the expected level across all early-learning goals.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","58105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661666","Department for Education","false","2017-01-09","<p>The answer in question 55853 quoted a complete closure of 14 secondary academies. PQ55854 quoted 2 closures. The difference is a result of one answer more tightly interpreting the definition of academies. The figures in PQ55853 include free schools, studio schools and UTCs, whereas PQ55854 excludes these school types.</p><p>There have been 2 complete closures of academy secondary schools, 2 free schools, 7 studio schools and 3 UTCs.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-01-09T15:56:57.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661666/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661666/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661666/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Academies: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answers of 8 December 2016 to Questions 55854 and 55853, on academy closures, for what reasons there is a difference between the number of academies that have been completely closed in those Answers.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","58100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661667","Department for Education","false","2017-01-11","<p>We want schools to provide all young people with a broad and balanced curriculum that equips them for success in adult life.</p><p> </p><p>High quality PSHE teaching has an important role to play in this, helping young people understand the world around them, building resilience and helping them to make positive choices and stay safe. We have made it clear in the introduction to the national curriculum that all schools should make provision for PSHE, drawing on examples of good practice. Academies and free schools are encouraged to teach PSHE as part of a broad and balanced curriculum.</p><p> </p><p>Sex education is already compulsory in secondary maintained schools, and the Government is clear that all schools should make provision for high quality, age-appropriate sex and relationship education (SRE) which is a vital part of preparing young people for life in modern Britain.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State agrees that we need to look again at the case for further action on PSHE and SRE provision, as a matter of priority with particular consideration to improving quality and accessibility. We are actively considering what steps we could take and will give a view soon.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-01-11T15:09:55.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661667/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661667/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661667/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Personal, Social, Health and Economic Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will bring forward legislative proposals to make provision for age-appropriate personal, social, health and economic education, including sex and relationships education, to be a statutory requirement for all schools; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","58120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661668","Department for Education","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear that tackling poverty and disadvantage, and delivering real social reform, is a priority for this Government. We are considering the future direction for children’s centres and will provide further detail in due course, including how stakeholders and members of the public can contribute.</p><p> </p><p>The requirement for Ofsted to undertake the inspections of Sure Start children’s centres is currently suspended pending consideration of their future direction as mentioned above.</p><p> </p><p>As indicated in the letter of 25 September 2015 to HM Chief Inspector of Education[1], the Secretary of State retains the ability to require Ofsted to undertake inspections under section 98A (1)(b) of the Childcare Act 2006, and that Ofsted itself retains the ability to inspect children’s centres under section 98A (2). We do not want this to affect the normal activity of children’s centres and expect them to continue their work to improve the outcomes for children and families in local areas, including their work on self-evaluation, monitoring and the collection of data. Those children’s centres that also deliver early years provision will continue to be inspected for that provision as part of the Common Inspection Framework.</p><p> </p><p>[1] This letter can be viewed at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/466149/Sam_Gyimah_letter_Ofsted_Inspection_of_Sure_Start_Children_s_Centres.pdf" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/466149/Sam_Gyimah_letter_Ofsted_Inspection_of_Sure_Start_Children_s_Centres.pdf</a></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-09T17:10:54.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661668/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661668/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661668/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Children's Centres: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Children and Education's letter to HM Chief Inspector of Education of 25 September 2015, on Ofsted Inspection of Sure Start Children's Centres, what steps she is taking to reinstate the inspection framework for Sure Start children's centres.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","58112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661669","Department for Education","false","2017-01-10","<p>The Department’s guidance on consultation sets out the minimum periods for which local authorities and academy trusts must consult, where school closure is proposed, but it does not mention pausing a consultation.</p><p>Consultation on a proposal to close a school is undertaken locally either by the local authority or the academy trust to allow those directly affected by the proposals to provide their comments.</p><p>It is up to the local authority or academy trust to decide whether a consultation needs to be paused. The Department does not record or hold this information centrally.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","58098 ; 58099","2017-01-10T13:12:40.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661669/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661669/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661669/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Schools: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 8 December 2016 to Question 55973, on school closures, whether the guidance her Department gives to academies on school closure consultations includes advice on pausing such consultations.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","58097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661670","Department for Education","false","2017-01-10","<p>The Department’s guidance on consultation sets out the minimum periods for which local authorities and academy trusts must consult, where school closure is proposed, but it does not mention pausing a consultation.</p><p>Consultation on a proposal to close a school is undertaken locally either by the local authority or the academy trust to allow those directly affected by the proposals to provide their comments.</p><p>It is up to the local authority or academy trust to decide whether a consultation needs to be paused. The Department does not record or hold this information centrally.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","58097 ; 58099","2017-01-10T13:12:40.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661670/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661670/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661670/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Schools: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 8 December 2016 to Question 55973, on school closures, on how many occasions a school closure consultation has been paused and that school subsequently closed down completely since 2015.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","58098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661671","Department for Education","false","2017-01-10","<p>The Department’s guidance on consultation sets out the minimum periods for which local authorities and academy trusts must consult, where school closure is proposed, but it does not mention pausing a consultation.</p><p>Consultation on a proposal to close a school is undertaken locally either by the local authority or the academy trust to allow those directly affected by the proposals to provide their comments.</p><p>It is up to the local authority or academy trust to decide whether a consultation needs to be paused. The Department does not record or hold this information centrally.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","58097 ; 58098","2017-01-10T13:12:40.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661671/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661671/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661671/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Schools: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 8 December 2016 to Question 55973, on school closures, for what reasons she would deem it necessary to pause a school closure consultation.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","58099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661672","Department for Education","false","2017-01-09","<p>The pilot of joint training for nominated single points of contact in schools and mental health services is being independently evaluated. The evaluation findings will be available in spring 2017 and will provide an assessment of the effectiveness of the pilot design and implementation, including its sustainability and potential for wider rollout. The evaluation is also looking at the extent to which the pilot resulted in delivery improvements, including in joint working practices between, and the timeliness and appropriateness of referrals from, schools to specialist mental health services; as well as any wider cultural and systems improvements.</p><p> </p><p>We have already shared some of the emerging practice from the pilot through national events, to inform local planning. We will use the formal evaluation findings to determine whether there is value in further roll out of specific training or models of single point of contact, and whether further testing is required of any aspects.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","58211","2017-01-09T16:43:04.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661672/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661672/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Schools: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what evaluation her Department has made of the Mental Health Services and Schools Link pilots; and what plans her Department has for those pilots to be extended.","false","Biography information for Nicky Morgan","Loughborough","Nicky Morgan","58087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661673","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-10","<p>As we start the process of leaving the EU, we will aim to deliver a stable and clear legislative framework for the continued effective management of chemicals, including maintaining standards that underpin trade and the protection of human health and the environment, and deliver on our international commitments.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-10T14:20:29.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661673/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661673/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661673/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Chemicals: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the application in the UK of standards under the REACH  regulation on the sale of chemicals.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","58077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661674","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-09","<p>On 14 December this year, Defra published new Greening Government Commitments for the period 2016 to 2020. This action builds on the previous set of commitments, so implementation is essentially already underway.</p><p> </p><p>Considerable progress has already been made. Between 2009-10 and 2014-15, the UK Government as a whole reduced its greenhouse gas emissions and waste by 22% each and its water consumption by 11%. The reporting framework was rolled forward during 2015-16 to enable further progress on the previous targets and to allow time to develop the new commitments. An annual report for 2015-16 is currently being prepared and we will continue to report on progress during the period covered by the new commitments.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-09T14:32:31.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661674/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661674/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661674/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress her Department has made on the roll-out of Greening Government Commitments for 2016-2020; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","58109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661675","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-11","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply given to the hon. Member for Crawley, Henry Smith, on 7 July 2016, PQ UIN905727.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-11T15:14:15.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661675/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661675/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","National Wildlife Crime Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the National Wildlife Crime Unit in tackling wildlife crime and protecting endangered species.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661676","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-10","<p>In the National Flood Resilience Review we prioritised looking at the greatest flood risks facing the country - river and coastal flooding. The government recognises that surface water flooding can also be a significant source of flooding and we will be considering this in more detail during 2017.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-10T14:24:31.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661676/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661676/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Flood Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when the Government plans to publish a Flood Resilience Review addressing the risks of flooding from surface water.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","58126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661677","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-10","<p>Year on year food prices have continued to fall, with a 2% fall over the last 12 months, according to the most recent official Consumer Prices Index (CPI) figures released on 13 December. General inflation is 1.2 per cent, up from 0.9 per cent in October. Food prices rose by 0.4% in the month to November 2016. However, overall, food prices have fallen by 7% since their peak in February 2014.</p><p> </p><p>Commodity prices, exchange rates and oil prices are known to be the most important drivers of retail food price inflation.</p><p> </p><p>This Government is committed to tackling poverty and disadvantage and to delivering real social reform, and we believe that economic growth and employment offer the best route to give people a better future. Household spend on food by households with the lowest 20% income is included in the Living Cost of Food Survey (LCFS) and has remained constant at around 16.5% for a number of years. The Government helps the most vulnerable afford and have access to nutritious food though initiatives such as the Healthy Start scheme and Free School Meals, and through the welfare system.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-01-10T14:55:40.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661677/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661677/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661677/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Food: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent assessment she has made of the effect of rising food prices on average household budgets.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","58127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661678","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-10","<p>Through the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) legal rules are in place to ensure that any international movement of trophies from the hunting of endangered species can only take place if the hunt is assessed as not having a detrimental impact on the survival of the species.</p><p> </p><p>In light of growing concerns about the sustainability of the hunting of some species, we have worked with EU Member States to introduce stricter controls on the importation of hunting trophies of certain endangered species, including lions and African elephants. As a result, the importation of hunting trophies of certain species from certain countries is currently prohibited.</p><p> </p><p>We have also been pressing for tough, transparent, global standards for the hunting of protected species. I attended the 17<sup>th</sup> meeting of the Conference of the Parties to CITES where Parties agreed to remove the loophole that allowed such trophies to be transported as personal effects. As a result, export permits will be needed for almost all hunted animals of endangered species included in Appendix II of CITES, including lions and African elephants, as well as those in Appendix I. Building on this, we agreed clear criteria the exporting country should consider when assessing that the hunt was both legal and sustainable before issuing an export permit.</p><p> </p><p>Finally, in the case of lions and African elephants, the UK has to then confirm that we agree with this assessment and issue a corresponding permit before any import can take place. As a result, we secured greater scrutiny of trade in trophies to ensure the sustainability of exports.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to monitor the impact of trophy hunting and will work to put in place greater protection, including prohibiting imports, if this is shown to be needed.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","58129","2017-01-10T14:58:55.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661678/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661678/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Hunting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to help prevent the hunting to extinction of endangered species.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661679","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-10","<p>Through the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) legal rules are in place to ensure that any international movement of trophies from the hunting of endangered species can only take place if the hunt is assessed as not having a detrimental impact on the survival of the species.</p><p> </p><p>In light of growing concerns about the sustainability of the hunting of some species, we have worked with EU Member States to introduce stricter controls on the importation of hunting trophies of certain endangered species, including lions and African elephants. As a result, the importation of hunting trophies of certain species from certain countries is currently prohibited.</p><p> </p><p>We have also been pressing for tough, transparent, global standards for the hunting of protected species. I attended the 17<sup>th</sup> meeting of the Conference of the Parties to CITES where Parties agreed to remove the loophole that allowed such trophies to be transported as personal effects. As a result, export permits will be needed for almost all hunted animals of endangered species included in Appendix II of CITES, including lions and African elephants, as well as those in Appendix I. Building on this, we agreed clear criteria the exporting country should consider when assessing that the hunt was both legal and sustainable before issuing an export permit.</p><p> </p><p>Finally, in the case of lions and African elephants, the UK has to then confirm that we agree with this assessment and issue a corresponding permit before any import can take place. As a result, we secured greater scrutiny of trade in trophies to ensure the sustainability of exports.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to monitor the impact of trophy hunting and will work to put in place greater protection, including prohibiting imports, if this is shown to be needed.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","58128","2017-01-10T14:58:55.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661679/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661679/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661679/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Animal Products: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to prohibit the importation of trophies secured from the killing of (a) lions, (b) elephants and (c) other mammals in African countries.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661680","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Government works with a range of governments and international organisations on the conservation of endangered species, including elephants and rhino, through a number of fora. This includes the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES) which protects around 35,000 species from unsustainable international trade. I attended the CITES Conference of Parties held in Johannesburg from 24 September to 5 October 2016, where the UK, working with the Member States of the European Union and other countries, played a major role in achieving strong outcomes for a number of species, including elephants and rhinos, that will help ensure their survival in the wild.</p><p> </p><p>Poaching is a major threat to elephants, rhino and other species and the UK has played a leading role in efforts to combat the illegal wildlife trade. The UK was represented by the Secretary of State at the Illegal Wildlife Trade Vietnam conference, on 17-18 November 2016 in Hanoi, where new concrete actions to deliver on the commitments agreed at the previous London and Botswana conferences in 2014 and 2015 were secured. In addition, the Secretary of State announced an additional £13 million for measures tackling the illegal wildlife trade, doubling our investment.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-11T13:09:29.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661680/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661680/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661680/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Wildlife: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to prevent further reductions in the world populations of elephants, rhinos and other species.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661681","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-11","<p>Prime Ministers David Cameron and Narendra Modi met in London in November 2015 and issued a joint statement in which they resolved to work together to improve protection for both captive and wild Asian elephants. There have been no discussions with the Indian Government specifically on banning the use of elephants in tourist attractions or preventing the capturing and breaking of young elephants for use in the tourism industry. However, further official level discussions have taken place with the Indian High Commission to discuss the joint statement and discuss specific areas on which we might work constructively beyond international fora such as the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES).</p><p> </p><p>Within CITES the UK has led on securing agreement to measures to increase focus on protecting Asian elephants. These include the strengthening of national legislation and enforcement to combat illegal trade in live Asian elephants, for range countries to develop strategies to manage their captive domestic populations and to develop and apply a regional registration and marking system covering domestic Asian elephants.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","58132 ; 58133","2017-01-11T13:22:21.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661681/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661681/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661681/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Elephants: India","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with the government of India on the conservation of Asian elephants and the potential merits of banning the use of elephants in tourist attractions.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661682","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-11","<p>Prime Ministers David Cameron and Narendra Modi met in London in November 2015 and issued a joint statement in which they resolved to work together to improve protection for both captive and wild Asian elephants. There have been no discussions with the Indian Government specifically on banning the use of elephants in tourist attractions or preventing the capturing and breaking of young elephants for use in the tourism industry. However, further official level discussions have taken place with the Indian High Commission to discuss the joint statement and discuss specific areas on which we might work constructively beyond international fora such as the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES).</p><p> </p><p>Within CITES the UK has led on securing agreement to measures to increase focus on protecting Asian elephants. These include the strengthening of national legislation and enforcement to combat illegal trade in live Asian elephants, for range countries to develop strategies to manage their captive domestic populations and to develop and apply a regional registration and marking system covering domestic Asian elephants.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","58131 ; 58132","2017-01-11T13:22:21.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661682/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661682/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Elephants: India","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to support the Indian government in protecting Asian elephants.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661683","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-10","<p>The UK Government is committed to tackling the crisis facing the African elephant from poaching and illegal trafficking. We fully support the existing global ban on ivory trade. The UK has discussed the global level of protection afforded to the elephant with EU Member States on numerous occasions. In particular, the proposal submitted to the 17<sup>th</sup> meeting of the Conference of Parties (CoP17) to the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) to include all populations of African elephant in Appendix I was debated in EU CITES meetings in preparation for CoP17.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-10T16:08:30.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661683/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661683/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661683/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Elephants: India","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with her EU counterparts on ensuring elephants are given the highest level of international protection.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661684","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-11","<p>The UK takes the conservation of lions seriously. There are strict controls in place for international trade in wild lion parts; however the Government currently has no plans to promote a ban on trade of captive lion parts.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-11T15:06:46.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661684/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661684/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Lions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to promote a ban on trade of captive lion parts.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661685","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-11","<p>At the Conference of the Parties to the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) earlier this year, it was decided that lions should not be uplisted to Appendix I of the Convention. The Government supported this decision.</p><p> </p><p>Based on the biological and other listing criteria under CITES, our assessment is that the entire lion population of Africa does not currently meet the criteria for inclusion in Appendix I. This is notably the case for Southern African lion populations, which have an increasing population trend.</p><p> </p><p>The UK takes the conservation of lions seriously. At the CITES Conference of the Parties, the UK played an instrumental role in banning the trade in wild lion bones, which represents a key conservation concern. We also supported a broad range of decisions to support African lion conservation on a continent-wide basis.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-11T15:09:32.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661685/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661685/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661685/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Lions: Africa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to promote the up-listing of African lions to Appendix 1 of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661686","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-11","<p>I met the Chinese delegation to the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) Conference of Parties in London immediately before the conference which was held in Johannesburg from 24 September to 5 October 2016. We discussed the conservation of a number of species including tigers.</p><p> </p><p>At the Conference, the UK, working with the Member States of the European Union and other countries, achieved strong outcomes for tigers including agreement to proposed decisions to scrutinise captive breeding facilities, and a regional photographic repository of seized tiger skins to aid enforcement action.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-11T15:12:10.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661686/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661686/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661686/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Tigers: China","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to support the Chinese government in protecting tigers.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661687","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-11","<p>Clare Moriarty (Permanent Secretary) is the diversity champion on Defra’s departmental board.</p><p> </p><p>The Government introduced diversity champions as part of the Talent Action Plan (TAP) commitment to have champions in all departments. The Government uses diversity champions to provide an overall insight for all protected characteristics, including LGBT, Race, Religion or Belief, Gender, Disability, Social Mobility, Age, Carers, Gender Reassignment etc.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-01-11T15:17:20.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661687/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661687/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661687/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, who the diversity champion is on her departmental board.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","58234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661688","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-11","<p>The UK has a strong record as a global leader in the fight against the illegal wildlife trade (IWT), and remains committed to working to bring an end to this scourge.</p><p> </p><p>We intend to use the additional £13 million in UK funding announced on 17 November to tackle IWT through a number of new initiatives to reduce demand, strengthen enforcement and develop sustainable livelihoods for communities affected by IWT. This is likely to include expanded British Military training for African park rangers; additional funding for Interpol to expand its work with key nations, tracking and intercepting illegal shipments of ivory, rhino horn and other illegal wildlife products; and up to £4million for the International Consortium for Combatting Wildlife Crime.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-11T12:18:11.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661688/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661688/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661688/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Wildlife: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, on what the additional £13 million to tackle the illegal wildlife trade announced in her Department's press release, UK leading global fight against illegal wildlife trade, published on 17 November 2016, will be spent.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661689","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-10","<p>The evidential base for the estimated packaging target recycling and recovery rates for 2018 and 2019 forms part of the Impact Assessments for consultations on packaging recycling and recovery targets, which can be found at: <a href="https://consult.defra.gov.uk/waste/packagingtargets2018-20" target="_blank">consult.defra.gov.uk/waste/packagingtargets2018-20</a>.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-10T16:05:30.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661689/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661689/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661689/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Packaging: Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2016 to Question 56277, what the evidential basis is for the target figures for 2018 and 2019; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","58201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661690","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-09","<p>I refer my hon. Friend to the reply given to my hon. Friend, the Member for St Ives, Derek Thomas, on 22 December 2016, PQ 57651.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-09T14:46:17.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661690/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661690/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661690/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Beverage Containers: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will assess the merits of introducing a deposit return system for plastic bottles.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","58340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661691","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-10","<p>All of the efficiency savings will be reinvested in the Government’s six year capital investment programme to better protect homes and businesses across England. The table below summarises the Environment Agency’s forecast for these efficiency savings:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>£39.4 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>£48.4 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018/19</p></td><td><p>£46.0 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2019/20</p></td><td><p>£43.9 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2020/21</p></td><td><p>£41.8 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-10T16:01:56.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661691/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661691/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661691/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Flood Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to paragraph 2.151 and table 1.10 of the Autumn Statement 2015, Cm 9162, how much in planned efficiency savings will fund the capital funding for flood protection in each year from 2016-17 to 2020-21.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","58346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661692","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-12","We welcomed the historic co-sponsorship by Sri Lanka of Resolution 30/1 at the UN Human Rights Council on 1 October 2015 committing it to reconciliation, accountability and the protection of human rights. While Sri Lanka has made progress against the commitments made in the resolution, much remains to be done. The High Commissioner for Human Rights will present his final progress report at the United Nations Human Rights Council (UNHRC) in March 2017. Our long standing position is that Sri Lanka should implement the commitments in Resolution 30/01, including its commitment to accountability. Ministers and senior officials have underlined the importance of Sri Lanka delivering in full on its UNHRC commitments in recent discussions with representatives of the Sri Lankan government and with our international partners. We have done so while recognising the scale of the challenge this represents and the importance of allowing time for credible, well thought out transitional justice mechanisms to be developed and implemented.","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-01-12T15:38:38.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661692/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661692/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661692/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-19","Sri Lanka: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the co-sponsored resolution on Sri Lanka at the 30th Session of the UN Human Rights Council held in October 2015, if he will make representations to the government of Sri Lanka to respect its commitments and allow international prosecutors to investigate allegations of violations of international humanitarian law in that country; and if he will encourage his international counterparts to make similar such representations.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","58271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661693","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>The Ascension Island Government's new Biosecurity Officer is working to strengthen biosecurity measures for the Island. As part of this, key stakeholders, including those involved in the runway resurfacing, will be consulted, in order to ensure that future imports will not risk introducing new species that could have a negative impact on the island's important biodiversity, or pose a threat to human health.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-12T15:48:50.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661693/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661693/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661693/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-19","Ascension Island: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what biosecurity standards apply to equipment and construction materials imported into Ascension Island in order to resurface the island runway.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","58275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661694","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>We have concerns about human rights and freedoms in Tibet. We have not raised these specific cases with the Chinese Government. However, the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson), raised our concerns about human rights in Tibet with the Chinese Government at the UK-China Strategic Dialogue on 20 December. We also raised our concerns about Tibet and a number of individuals with the Chinese Government at the UK-China Human Rights Dialogue on 27 October. I attended the opening of the dialogue. We have recently received information on the sentencing of these individuals, and are in touch with our Embassy in Beijing to obtain further details.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-01-09T15:38:22.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661694/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661694/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661694/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-19","China: Buddhism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterpart in China on sentencing of Drugdra, Lobsang Khedrub, Lobsang Gephel, Lodro, Ta're Kyi, Bonkho Kyi, Tsultrim (Trotsik Tsultrim), Tsultrim (Tsulte), Akyakya and Losang Sonam for their involvement in the Dalai Lama's 80th birthday celebrations.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","58314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661695","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-09","The Government has repeatedly raised concerns about the plight of the Rohingya community in Burma. I last raised this when I met the Burmese Minister of Construction on 29 November. The Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my noble Friend, the Rt Hon. Baroness Anelay of St Johns DBE also raised our concerns when she visited Burma from 9-12 November. We are particularly concerned for the welfare of the estimated 3,400 children who were suffering from severe acute malnutrition prior to the flare up in violence in Rakhine following the 9 October attacks on the Burmese border posts. We have called on the Government of Burma to resume immediately humanitarian aid and to conduct an independent investigation into allegations of human rights violations. The Investigation Commission has now been established and will report back by 31 January 2017.","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-01-09T15:24:20.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661695/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661695/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661695/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-19","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to protect (a) the Rohingya population in Myanmar and (b) children in that community.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","58202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661696","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office Board Diversity Champion is Karen Pierce, Chief Operating Officer.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-12T15:49:27.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661696/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661696/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661696/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-19","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, who the diversity champion is on his departmental board.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","58236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661697","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>Neither I nor The Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwelath Affairs, my Noble Friend, the Rt Hon. the Baroness Anelay of St Johns, the FCO Minister with responsibility for the Overseas Territories, have had discussions with the Cayman Islands government about the Cayman Turtle Centre (previously known as the Cayman Turtle Farm). Responsibility for animal welfare and tourism, including policies governing the Cayman Turtle Centre, is devolved to the elected government of the Cayman Islands under the terms of their Constitution.</p><p>FCO travel advice provides information and advice to help British nationals have a trouble-free time abroad. It does not offer information and advice on ethical issues such as the practice of keeping animals in captivity.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-12T16:02:04.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661697/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661697/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661697/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-19","Cayman Islands: Turtles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will take steps to ensure that British citizens travelling to the Cayman Islands are aware of the practice of farming the Cayman Turtle for use in the tourism industry.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661698","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>Neither I nor The Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Noble Friend, the Rt Hon. Baroness Anelay of St Johns, the FCO Minister with responsibility for the Overseas Territories, have had discussions with the Cayman Islands government about farming the Cayman Turtle for meat and tourist entertainment. Responsibility for animal welfare and tourism, is devolved to the elected government of the Cayman Islands under the terms of their Constitution.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-12T15:57:23.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661698/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661698/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661698/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-19","Cayman Islands: Turtles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Cayman Island counterpart on preventing the practice of farming the Cayman Turtle for meat and tourist entertainment.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661699","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-11","<p>Iran's ballistic missile programme remains a significant concern. UN Security Council Resolution 2231 calls upon Iran to not undertake activity related to ballistic missiles designed to be capable of delivering nuclear weapons, and we urge Iran to abide by this. We keep Iran's ballistic missile programme under constant review and we remain committed to enforcing all international restrictions on it.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-11T16:19:31.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661699/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661699/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661699/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-19","Iran: Guided Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment the Government has made of Iran's ballistic missile programme.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","58172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661700","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-13","<p>We receive regular updates from our posts in Tel Aviv and Jerusalem regarding the situation in Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territories. We welcome the recent period of relative calm which stands in contrast to the upsurge in terrorist violence seen during the past year.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-13T13:38:49.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661700/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661700/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661700/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-19","Israel and West Bank: Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on recent violence in Israel and the West Bank.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","58173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661701","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-13","<p>I refer the hon. Member to my answer to my answer of 07 December 2016 (written PQ 55458).</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-13T13:32:40.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661701/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661701/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661701/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-19","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports he has received on renewed tunnel building into Israel by Hamas in Gaza.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","58174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661702","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-13","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to my previous response of 15 November 2016 (PQ 52043).</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-13T13:40:34.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661702/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661702/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661702/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-19","Hezbollah: Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports he has received on the size of Hezbollah's weapons arsenal.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","58175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661703","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Government continues to have concerns about human rights in Eritrea, in particular shortcomings in the rule of law, indefinite national service, freedom of expression and religion, and level of cooperation with international human rights bodies such as the UN Special Rapporteur on human rights in Eritrea. Eritrea remains listed as a Human Rights Priority Country in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office Annual Human Rights Report 2015.</p><p>The Government is clear in our engagement with Eritrea about the tangible improvements in its human rights record we want to see. We urge Eritrea to implement the recommendations from its 2014 Universal Periodic Review and welcome Eritrea's recent agreement to work with the UN Development Programme to take forward these recommendations.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-13T13:40:43.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661703/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661703/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661703/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-19","Eritrea: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment the Government has made of the human rights situation in Eritrea.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","58206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661704","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-11","<p>Prime Ministers David Cameron and Narendra Modi met in London in November 2015 and issued a joint statement in which they resolved to work together to improve protection for both captive and wild Asian elephants. There have been no discussions with the Indian Government specifically on banning the use of elephants in tourist attractions or preventing the capturing and breaking of young elephants for use in the tourism industry. However, further official level discussions have taken place with the Indian High Commission to discuss the joint statement and discuss specific areas on which we might work constructively beyond international fora such as the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES).</p><p> </p><p>Within CITES the UK has led on securing agreement to measures to increase focus on protecting Asian elephants. These include the strengthening of national legislation and enforcement to combat illegal trade in live Asian elephants, for range countries to develop strategies to manage their captive domestic populations and to develop and apply a regional registration and marking system covering domestic Asian elephants.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","58131 ; 58133","2017-01-11T13:22:21.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661704/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661704/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661704/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Elephants: India","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with her Indian counterpart on preventing the practice of capturing and breaking young elephants in India for use in the tourism industry.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661705","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office does not hold records of the numbers of British nationals who visit Eritrea.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-13T13:58:54.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661705/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661705/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661705/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-19","Eritrea: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what estimate he has made of the number of UK nationals who have visited Eritrea in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","58203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661706","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>​The FCO's Official Development Assistance (ODA) allocation for FY 2016/17 is £466m.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-12T15:51:53.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661706/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661706/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661706/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-19","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much of his Department's spending falls under the definition of official development assistance in the current financial year.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","58125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661707","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>Getting humanitarian aid to Syrians trapped in besieged areas is one of our top priorities. Over 570,000 people remain in areas besieged by the Syrian regime. We have regular discussions with our international partners, including on methods for delivering humanitarian assistance to besieged populations in Syria. There are huge obstacles to carrying out airdrops, not least the risk to aircraft from regime air defences or terrorist groups. However, we rule nothing out and maintain every effort to help those in besieged areas. Most recently on 19 December we helped secure UN Security Council Resolution 2328 which demanded full access for the UN across Syria.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-12T15:32:08.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661707/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661707/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661707/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-19","Syria: International Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will take steps to discuss with his international counterparts plans to expedite air drops in Syria.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","58123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661708","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) has discussed issues relating to the continued export of arms from the UK to Saudi Arabia regularly with his counterpart, including most recently during his visit to Riyadh on 11 December 2016 and again on 15 December 2016.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-11T16:16:17.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661708/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661708/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661708/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-19","Saudi Arabia: Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterpart in Saudi Arabia on future arms deals with the UK.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","58124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661709","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>Ministers and officials have repeatedly made representations on all consular cases involving British nationals in Iran, including Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe's, at all levels, with the Iranian Government. I personally raised these cases when I met the Iranian Ambassador on 7 December and our Ambassador in Iran will continue to raise these cases with the Iranian Government at every available opportunity in Tehran.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-12T15:13:18.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661709/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661709/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661709/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-19","Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent steps he has taken to provide assistance to Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","58088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661710","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Manual for Prescribed Specialised Services 2016/17 describes which elements of specialised services are commissioned by NHS England and which by clinical commissioning groups (CCGs). For specialist cancer services, the Manual makes clear that CCGs are responsible for commissioning adjuvant drug treatments, for example, drugs affecting bone metabolism including bisphosphonates. The Manual is available at:</p><p><a href="http://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2016/06/pss-manual-may16.pdf" target="_blank">www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2016/06/pss-manual-may16.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Decisions about the commissioning and funding of bisphosphonates for the treatment and prevention of secondary breast cancer are taken by local CCGs which are best placed to know what local need exists.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-11T11:05:19.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661710/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661710/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661710/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Breast Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he has taken to raise awareness among clinical commissioning groups of their responsibilities related to the commissioning of bisphosphonates for the indication and prevention of secondary breast cancer.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","58086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661711","Department of Health","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Department holds quarterly meetings with the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA) at which the Authority’s performance against its statutory duties is discussed. Outside of these meetings, officials have daily contact with members of the HFEA’s Executive on a range of business matters. The Department also has observer status at all meetings of the full Authority, the HFEA’s Audit and Governance Committee and the Scientific and Clinical Advances Advisory Committee.</p><p> </p><p>The HFEA’s regulatory duties, as determined by the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Act 1990, apply equally to fertility clinics in the NHS and independent sectors.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-09T16:39:16.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661711/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661711/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661711/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Fertility: Clinics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with what frequency his Department assesses the work of the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority's regulation of private fertility clinics; and when the last such assessment was conducted.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","58092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661712","Department of Health","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA) is assessing the report by the Centre for Evidence-based Medicine. The study concluded that many fertility centres in the United Kingdom offer a range of add-ons in addition to standard in-vitro fertilisation procedures and, for many, claims of benefit are made. However, in most cases, the claims are not quantified and evidence is not cited to support the claims. The review concludes that there is a need for more information on add-ons to be made available by fertility clinics to support well-informed treatment decisions.</p><p> </p><p>The care offered in licensed fertility clinics is primarily a matter for the national regulator, the HFEA. The HFEA currently publishes information for patients about some add-on procedures and is committed to introducing a simple labelling system on its new website to highlight the risks and benefits of a wide range of treatment add-ons.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-09T16:30:25.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661712/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661712/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661712/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Fertility: Clinics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make an assessment of the implications for his Department's policies of the findings on IVF add-on procedures of the report by the Centre for Evidence-based Medicine, Lack of Evidence for interventions offered in UK fertility centres, published on 28 November 2016; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","58111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661713","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>Therapists working in general practice will be a mix of trainees and experienced therapists and will be part of integrated services in primary care, working in multi-disciplinary teams in general practices. Existing providers will employ new therapists and they will be deployed, along with experienced therapists, into general practices. The first new integrated services will start in 2017. The exact therapist numbers within each clinical commissioning group is to be determined locally.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-11T12:25:00.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661713/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661713/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661713/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Mental Health Services: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the GP Forward Review published in April 2016, how many of the 3,000 mental health therapists will have been employed by the end of each year to 2020.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661714","Department for Education","false","2017-01-09","<p>The pilot of joint training for nominated single points of contact in schools and mental health services is being independently evaluated. The evaluation findings will be available in spring 2017 and will provide an assessment of the effectiveness of the pilot design and implementation, including its sustainability and potential for wider rollout. The evaluation is also looking at the extent to which the pilot resulted in delivery improvements, including in joint working practices between, and the timeliness and appropriateness of referrals from, schools to specialist mental health services; as well as any wider cultural and systems improvements.</p><p> </p><p>We have already shared some of the emerging practice from the pilot through national events, to inform local planning. We will use the formal evaluation findings to determine whether there is value in further roll out of specific training or models of single point of contact, and whether further testing is required of any aspects.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","58087","2017-01-09T16:43:04.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661714/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661714/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661714/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Mental Health Services: Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what evaluation her Department has made of the Mental Health Services and Schools Link Pilots; and what plans she has to extend those pilots.","false","Biography information for Nicky Morgan","Loughborough","Nicky Morgan","58211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661715","Department of Health","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Better Care Fund (BCF), first announced in Spending Round 2013, and implemented from the beginning of 2015-16, is the first national, mandatory integration policy. One of its overarching aims is to keep people living independently at home and in their communities, including those who are disabled and of working age.</p><p> </p><p>The Integration and Better Care Fund Policy Framework for 2017-19, due to be published early in the New Year, sets out proposals for going beyond the BCF towards further integration by 2020. Although there will be no separate process for integration plans, local areas will set out how they expect to progress to further integration by 2020 in their BCF 17-19 returns. We will provide a set of resources, integration models and indicators for integration to help local areas. However, it will be up to local areas how they use the fund to benefit their population.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-09T16:31:34.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661715/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661715/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661715/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Health Services and Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to paragraph 1.4 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015 on local plans for health and social care integration, what steps the Government and NHS England are taking to ensure that (a) the needs of working age disabled people and (b) outcomes related to independent living are included in those plans.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","58219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661716","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Government welcomes the publication in November 2016 of the Cancer Research UK, Testing times to come: an evaluation of pathology capacity in the UK. Pathology services play a major role in the diagnosis and treatment of cancer, as well as many other conditions.</p><p> </p><p>The Department’s national delivery partners are working to modernise the delivery of pathology services in the National Health Service in England, and reviewing the workforce and training that will be required in the future.</p><p> </p><p>Health is a devolved matter in the rest of the United Kingdom.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-11T12:09:46.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661716/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661716/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661716/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Pathology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the implications for (a) his and (b) the NHS's policies of the findings of Cancer Research UK's report entitled, Testing times to come: an evaluation of pathology capacity in the UK, published in November 2016.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","58176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661717","Department of Health","false","2017-01-09","<p>This information is not collected centrally.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-09T16:20:17.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661717/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661717/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661717/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Orthopaedics: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many child amputees there were in each of the past five years.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","58214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661718","Department of Health","false","2017-01-09","<p>Pathology services play a major role in the diagnosis and treatment of cancer, as well as many other conditions. The National Health Service in England spends an estimated £2.5 to £3.0 billion annually on these services, and employs over 2,600 consultant pathologists. The Department’s national delivery partners are working to modernise the delivery of pathology services, and reviewing the workforce and training that will be required in the future.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-09T18:07:55.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661718/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661718/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661718/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Pathology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the availability of pathology services.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","58212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661719","Department of Health","false","2017-01-09","<p>Health is a devolved matter in the United Kingdom and so the question of the resources available for pathology services in Northern Ireland is a matter for Northern Ireland’s Minister of Health.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-09T18:02:47.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661719/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661719/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661719/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Pathology: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent discussions he has had with Northern Ireland's Minister of Health on the resources available for pathology services.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","58213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661720","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Department of Health is committed to promoting and achieving equality and diversity in the workplace. We aim to attract and retain people who are the best in their field, with the right skills and competencies and from a diverse range of backgrounds. This diversity makes the Department better able to serve the citizens of the United Kingdom.</p><p> </p><p>The Departmental Board has appointed the Diversity Champions shown in the table below</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Diversity Topic</p></td><td><p>Board Champion</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Race</p></td><td><p>Lee McDonough</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Gender</p></td><td><p>Tamara Finkelstein</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>LGBT</p></td><td><p>Clara Swinson</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Disability</p></td><td><p>David Williams</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Social Mobility</p></td><td><p>Mark Davies</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Health and Wellbeing</p></td><td><p>Gina Radford</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-11T13:43:14.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661720/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661720/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661720/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Department of Health: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, who the diversity champion is on his departmental board.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","58237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661721","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>Details of all Ministerial meetings with external stakeholders are published quarterly in arrears on the GOV.UK website. The latest publication up to the end of September 2016 is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ministerial-gifts-hospitality-travel-and-external-meetings-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ministerial-gifts-hospitality-travel-and-external-meetings-2016</a></p><p> </p><p>Details of meetings between Department officials and external stakeholders are not collected centrally.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-11T11:16:32.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661721/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661721/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661721/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Obesity: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, who he, his ministerial colleagues and officials have met since 18 August 2016 to discuss Childhood Obesity: a plan for action, published on that date.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","58162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661722","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>NHS England’s Accelerate, Co-ordinate, Evaluate (ACE) programme is testing innovative ways of diagnosing cancer earlier. Wave 1 of this programme incorporated 60 projects looking at a number of different initiatives, including offering patients the option to self-refer for diagnostic tests; lowering referral thresholds for general practitioners; and multi-disciplinary diagnostic centres where patients can have several tests in the same place on the same day.</p><p> </p><p>The ACE programme is currently testing and evaluating these new approaches.</p><p> </p><p>The results of the evaluation of wave 1 of the ACE programme are expected to be available shortly, and will inform the work of the national cancer programme to implement the recommendations of the independent Cancer Taskforce.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","58159","2017-01-11T11:55:12.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661722/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661722/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661722/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made in the building of 60 new multi-disciplinary centres for cancer diagnosis, announced by NHS England in January 2015.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","58158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661723","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>NHS England’s Accelerate, Co-ordinate, Evaluate (ACE) programme is testing innovative ways of diagnosing cancer earlier. Wave 1 of this programme incorporated 60 projects looking at a number of different initiatives, including offering patients the option to self-refer for diagnostic tests; lowering referral thresholds for general practitioners; and multi-disciplinary diagnostic centres where patients can have several tests in the same place on the same day.</p><p> </p><p>The ACE programme is currently testing and evaluating these new approaches.</p><p> </p><p>The results of the evaluation of wave 1 of the ACE programme are expected to be available shortly, and will inform the work of the national cancer programme to implement the recommendations of the independent Cancer Taskforce.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","58158","2017-01-11T11:55:12.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661723/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661723/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661723/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he plans to implement the cancer diagnosis test self-referral system, proposed by NHS England in January 2015.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","58159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661724","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>Public Health England (PHE) is responsible for the sugar reduction and wider reformulation programme, a key commitment in the Government’s Childhood Obesity Plan. PHE will work with all sectors of the food industry (retailers, manufacturers and the eating out of the home sector) to reduce the amount of sugar in the foods that contribute most to children’s diets by 20% by 2020, with a 5% reduction in the first year. This initially focuses the programme on yoghurts, biscuits, cakes, morning goods (for example croissants and pastries), puddings, ice-cream, breakfast cereals, confectionery and sweet spreads. Products that are intended for consumption by babies and young children are included in PHE’s programme and will be considered in further detail in spring 2017. Infant formula is excluded from this programme since its composition is governed by legislation.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-11T11:11:44.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661724/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661724/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661724/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Sugar: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made in reducing the sugar content of products for babies and young children.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","58157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661725","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Government is developing a new tobacco control plan, which we will be publishing shortly. The plan will focus on tackling health inequalities and supporting priority groups, including people with mental health problems, where smoking rates remain high.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","58196","2017-01-11T11:08:59.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661725/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661725/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661725/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Tobacco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when his Department plans to publish the next Tobacco Control Plan for England.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","58197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661726","Department of Health","false","2017-01-09","<p>No such assessment has been made.</p><p> </p><p>The strategy and its companion document provide excellent advice to the National Health Service on implementing changes at a local level to improve the management and care of people with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and asthma. Elements of the strategy have been incorporated into the NHS outcomes framework and have been used to develop the national COPD and asthma audits, the forthcoming best practice tariff for COPD and the smoking cessation Commissioning for Quality and Innovation payment.</p><p> </p><p>The Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) Outcomes Indicator Set also includes indicators to support CCGs to understand the progress they are making in improving outcomes for people with COPD.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-09T16:29:00.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661726/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661726/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661726/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Lung Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment has been made and against what criteria of the success of the July 2011 Outcomes Strategy for Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease and Asthma in England.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","58226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661727","Department of Health","false","2017-01-13","<p>Information is not available in the format requested. Future funding for local health services in Northumberland (which covers Wansbeck constituency) is a matter for NHS England.</p><p> </p><p>A full table setting out allocations to each clinical commissioning group for 2016-17 to 2020-21 is published on NHS England’s website and can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/ccg-allocations.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/ccg-allocations.pdf</a></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-13T14:24:40.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661727/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661727/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661727/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Health Services: Wansbeck","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much funding the Government plans to provide to which NHS services in Wansbeck constituency in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","58253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661728","Department of Health","false","2017-01-13","<p>Data for life expectancy, broken down by household income, is not routinely collected.</p><p> </p><p>Life expectancy is higher now than it has ever been for both men and women, and is generally increasing in most areas – including deprived areas, but inequalities remain.</p><p> </p><p>The Office for National Statistics publishes data on life expectancy broken down by deprivation decile. The latest available data, 2012-14, show that life expectancy for males in the most deprived decile is 74.1 years, compared with 83.2 years for males in the least deprived decile. For females it is 79.1 years in the most deprived decile, compared with 86.1 years in the least deprived decile.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-13T10:49:14.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661728/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661728/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661728/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Life Expectancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the estimated life expectancy is for people who earn (a) below and (b) above the average household income.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","58254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661730","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Government is developing a new tobacco control plan, which we will be publishing shortly. The plan will focus on tackling health inequalities and supporting priority groups, including people with mental health problems, where smoking rates remain high.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","58197","2017-01-11T11:08:59.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661730/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661730/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661730/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Smoking: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to reduce the disparity in smoking rates between people with and without mental health issues.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","58196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661731","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>Simon Stevens, Chief Executive of NHS England, announced on 6 December that £200 million would be available in 2017/18 and 2018/19 to support Cancer Alliances to develop their approach to earlier diagnosis and living with and beyond cancer. This will include investment both to make sure services are getting the most out of our existing capacity, and to support increases in diagnostic capacity. Cancer Alliances will be submitting bids for this funding through a ‘best possible value’ process. Although Cancer Alliances are free to include independent provision as part of their bid where they feel it is appropriate and meets the ‘best possible value’ criteria, it is not a requirement.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","58284","2017-01-11T11:58:45.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661731/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661731/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661731/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made in implementing the Five Year Forward View commitment to increasing cancer diagnostic capacity.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","58198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661732","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>There are no current plans for Ministers to meet the Agri-Food Technology Leadership Council or Food Innovation Network. Officials will continue to work with these groups and other stakeholders in the delivery of the Childhood Obesity Strategy.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-11T11:13:40.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661732/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661732/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661732/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Obesity: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 16 December 2016 to Question 57118, what plans he has to meet (a) the Food Innovation Network and (b) the Agri-Food Technology Council to discuss the delivery of the childhood obesity strategy.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","58290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661733","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Department has made no review of therapy provision at Nottingham University Hospitals NHS Trust. That is a matter for the local National Health Service.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England advises that Rushcliffe Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG), Nottingham North and East CCG, Nottingham City CCG and Nottingham West CCG this year undertook clinically-led reviews of services that fall outside the national tariff payment mechanism. The reviews were initiated because the CCGs need to ensure they are getting the best value for money when commissioning publicly funded health services.</p><p> </p><p>As part of this work, the CCGs identified some services currently delivered by Nottingham University Hospitals NHS Trust that could be delivered in a community setting, closer to patients’ homes, providing better value to the local NHS and capacity within local hospitals. The CCGs are committed to continuing to provide the three neurological services provided by the Trust as a single specialty neuro-rehabilitation service provided in the community. This will be supported by the same level of clinical expertise and care as is currently provided.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-11T11:40:14.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661733/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661733/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661733/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Neuromuscular Disorders: Physiotherapy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps are being taken to ensure physiotherapy is available to people with muscle-wasting conditions at Nottingham University Hospitals NHS Trust as a result of his Department's review of that hospital's therapy service provision.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","58258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661734","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>Enfield Clinical Commissioning Group is currently working with seven practices that have applied for funding through the General Practice Resilience Programme, of whom four have been accepted and three are pending a decision.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is unable to release the names of the practices as this information is commercially sensitive.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-11T11:32:19.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661734/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661734/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661734/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","General Practitioners: Enfield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 13 December 2016 to Question 56221, if he will list the seven Enfield practices which have been identified for support under the General Practice Resilience Programme.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","58286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661735","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>Simon Stevens, Chief Executive of NHS England, announced on 6 December that £200 million would be available in 2017/18 and 2018/19 to support Cancer Alliances to develop their approach to earlier diagnosis and living with and beyond cancer. This will include investment both to make sure services are getting the most out of our existing capacity, and to support increases in diagnostic capacity. Cancer Alliances will be submitting bids for this funding through a ‘best possible value’ process. Although Cancer Alliances are free to include independent provision as part of their bid where they feel it is appropriate and meets the ‘best possible value’ criteria, it is not a requirement.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","58198","2017-01-11T11:58:44.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661735/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661735/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661735/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how the National Diagnostic Capacity Fund will support NHS commissioners and providers to utilise independent sector providers of diagnostic services.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","58284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661736","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>The numbers of medical assistants employed in general practice will be determined by individual employers. Health Education England (HEE) will begin work to pilot and evaluate the medical assistant role in 2017. HEE are also supporting an employer led Trailblazer Group which will enable the development of an apprentice route into this occupation.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-11T13:40:28.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661736/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661736/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661736/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many medical assistants he plans to introduce into general practice in each year until 2020.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661737","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>The current National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) guideline, Early and locally advanced breast cancer: diagnosis and management (CG80), makes the following recommendation:</p><p> </p><p>“Offer bisphosphonates to patients identified by algorithms 1 and 2 in ‘Guidance for the management of breast cancer treatment-induced bone loss: a consensus position statement from a UK expert group’ (2008) (see appendix 2 of the <a href="https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg80/evidence" target="_blank">full guideline page</a> 113).”</p><p> </p><p>NICE is currently updating this guidance and the use of adjuvant bisphosphonates has been identified as one of the key areas that will be covered in the update, which is scheduled for publication in July 2018.</p><p> </p><p>The guideline has been scheduled to take into account the latest available evidence on the adjuvant use of bisphosphonates for the treatment of breast cancer. In the absence of guidance from NICE, clinicians and commissioners should make decisions on the adjuvant use of bisphosphonates based on an assessment of the available evidence.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-11T10:58:50.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661737/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661737/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661737/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Breast Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential detriment to patients of NICE postponing until 2018 its decision on the use of bisphosphonates for breast cancer patients.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","58296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661738","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>The independent sector provides diagnostic services to the National Health Service which supports the NHS to meet waiting time standards for the diagnosis and treatment of cancer.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-11T12:06:22.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661738/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661738/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661738/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment the Government has made of the role of independent sector providers of diagnostic services in meeting NHS cancer diagnosis targets.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","58283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661739","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>The General Practice Resilience Programme is a four-year £40 million programme which devolves funding to NHS England’s 13 local teams to secure and deliver a wide menu of support to practices prioritised locally, against nationally set criteria.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is offering support to over a thousand general practices under the first wave of the General Practice Resilience Programme. The assessments carried out by NHS England local teams, concluded on 18 October 2016, identified 1,062 individual practices that will benefit from support this year to help improve sustainability and resilience, including support upstream of difficulties occurring. NHS England believe that the actual number to be offered support is likely to be greater, as some NHS England local teams are additionally targeting support across geographical areas more generally.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-11T12:22:19.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661739/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661739/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661739/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","General Practitioners: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of GP practices to receive support in 2016-17 under the General Practice Resilience Programme.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661740","Department of Health","false","2017-01-09","<p>The data requested for 2016-17 is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Information for 2011-12 through to 2015-16 on the total amount of current and capital expenditure on services by organisations in Yorkshire and the Humber is publically available on gov.uk as part of the Country and Regional Analysis statistical release. This information can be found at the following web link:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/country-and-regional-analysis-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/country-and-regional-analysis-2016</a></p><p> </p><p>A breakdown of total spending for the Department of Health group, including staff expenditure can be found in the <em>Department of Health’s Annual Report and Accounts</em>. The latest available being 2015-16, and reported in <em>Note 2.2 Department Group Expenditure Detail</em> on Page 136 following the web link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/539602/DH_Annual_Report_Web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/539602/DH_Annual_Report_Web.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-09T18:01:43.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661740/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661740/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661740/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Department of Health: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the value of (a) staffing expenditure, (b) other revenue costs and (c) capital expenditure by his Department and its arms-length bodies in whole or in part in Yorkshire and the Humber in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","58319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661741","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Government is in the process of preparing a draft consultation document and impact assessment in line with our intention to publicly consult on the future availability of homeopathic products in primary care.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-11T11:49:35.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661741/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661741/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661741/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-19","Homeopathy: Prescriptions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 13 December 2016 to Question 56390, what preparatory work has been done on the public consultation on the availability od homeopathic products in primary care to be announced in due course.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","58288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661742","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-01-09T16:09:27.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661742/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661742/answer","CO-DC00-PRN01_Rayhan Ali_4224_001.pdf","UKSA Response to PQ58339","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661742/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-19","Suicide: York","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many recorded suicides there have been in York in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","58339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661743","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-13","The Government believes that prisons should be places of safety and reform. As part of this, reducing the incidence of suicide is a key priority. Our recent White Paper sets out the specific steps that we are taking to improve safety. They include investing over £100m to recruit an additional 2,500 staff across the estate by the end of 2018. The National Offender Management Service has launched a suicide and self-harm reduction project, led by an experienced prison governor, which is driving work in this area. This includes implementing the recommendations of a review of the Assessment, Care in Custody and Teamwork (ACCT) process, the multi-disciplinary case management process that is the main tool for managing prisoners at risk of suicide and self-harm. Providing the right intervention and treatment is vital to improving the outcomes for people who are in distress, and all prisons have established procedures in place to identify, manage and support people at risk of suicide or self-harm. But we recognise that more can be done. That is why we have invested in specialist mental health training for prison officers and allocated more funding for prison safety. These improvements and reforms will benefit prisoners who are vulnerable, suffering from mental health problems or at risk of committing suicide.","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-01-13T15:08:05.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661743/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661743/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661743/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-19","Prisoners: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps she is taking to reduce the incidence of suicide in prisons.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","58329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661744","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Home Office does not hold data centrally on how police funding is allocated to the firearms licensing department of forces in England and Wales, nor the number of officers and staff who are employed in firearms licensing departments. Data are published on the primary function of officers and staff, but these do not allow firearms licensing roles to be separately identified.</p><p>The deployment of available resources is an operational decision for Chief Officers, working with their Police and Crime Commissioner.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","58324","2017-01-09T13:51:53.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661744/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661744/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661744/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-19","Firearms: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much funding was allocated to the firearms licensing department of each police authority area in England and Wales in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr Ian Liddell-Grainger","Bridgwater and West Somerset","Mr Ian Liddell-Grainger","58323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661745","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Home Office does not hold data centrally on how police funding is allocated to the firearms licensing department of forces in England and Wales, nor the number of officers and staff who are employed in firearms licensing departments. Data are published on the primary function of officers and staff, but these do not allow firearms licensing roles to be separately identified.</p><p>The deployment of available resources is an operational decision for Chief Officers, working with their Police and Crime Commissioner.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","58323","2017-01-09T13:51:53.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661745/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661745/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661745/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-19","Firearms: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many police (a) officers and (b) civilian staff were employed in firearms licensing departments in each police authority area in England and Wales in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr Ian Liddell-Grainger","Bridgwater and West Somerset","Mr Ian Liddell-Grainger","58324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661746","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>All institutions that sponsor Tier 4 students are required to undergo an annual basic compliance assessment. In the period May 2010 to September 2016, 968 institutions have had their Tier 4 sponsor status revoked. This number does not include those institutions that failed their basic compliance assessment but retained their licences after having had discretion applied. It does include those that have subsequently had their licences reinstated. The list of current sponsors on the Tier 4 register is updated daily and is available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/578935/2016-12-19_Tier_4_Register_of_Sponsors.pdf</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-09T13:54:41.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661746/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661746/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661746/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-19","Overseas Students: Entry Clearances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 8 December 2016 to Question 55996, how many universities do not stick to the rules.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","58285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661747","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The additional £10 million funding package for those arriving under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement (VPR) and Vulnerable Children’s Resettlement (VCR) Schemes is for adults only (age 19+). This funding is coming jointly from the Department for Education’s (DfE) Adult Education budget and from the Syrian Resettlement Programme budget.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-09T13:55:30.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661747/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661747/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661747/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-19","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will take steps to ensure that 16 to 18 year olds are eligible to benefit from the additional £10 million funding for English language teaching for resettled (a) Syrian and (b) other Vulnerable Children's Resettlement Scheme refugees.","false","Biography information for Caroline Ansell","Eastbourne","Caroline Ansell","58261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661748","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>In accordance with the statement of requirements, contractors provide reports to the Home Office on specified incidents within specified timescales. The Home Office does not record reports by complaint type and therefore this information could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-09T13:51:14.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661748/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661748/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661748/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-19","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 16 June 2016 to Question 38987, how many complaints have been made under paragraphs 4.5.1.2 and 4.5.1.3 of schedule 2 of the Compass contracts by complaint type and Compass region in each year since 2013.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","58248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661749","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Home Office does not record complaints by complainant or by complaint type, therefore this information could only be obtained at disproportionate cost. Where allegations are made that relate to criminal behaviour the Home Office will ensure that the allegation is raised with the relevant police force for them to investigate.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-09T13:54:20.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661749/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661749/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661749/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-19","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many allegations against asylum accommodation users of (a) assault, (b) damage to property and (c) anti-social behaviour have been reported to her Department by G4S in connection with the operation of Compass asylum accommodation contracts since 2013; how many such allegations have been investigated by her Department or another independent body; and what the outcomes were of such investigations.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","58149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661750","Home Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>The Home Office Executive Management Board chaired by the Permanent Secretary and made up of Director Generals and the Second Permanent Secretary have all agreed to be diversity and inclusion champions for respective protected characteristics as detailed below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Diversity Strand/ Protected Characteristic</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Home Office Champion </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Disability</p></td><td><p>Mark Thomson, Director General, Her Majesty’s Passport Office and United Kingdom Visas and Immigration</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Generational diversity</p></td><td><p>Paul Lincoln, Director General, Crime, Policing and Fire Group</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Race</p></td><td><p>Mark Sedwill, Permanent Secretary, Hugh Ind (Chair of Race Board)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Gender</p></td><td><p>Patsy Wilkinson, Second Permanent Secretary</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sexual Orientation</p></td><td><p>Mike Parsons, Director General, Capabilities and Resources</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Faith</p></td><td><p>Tom Hurd, Director General, Office of Security and Counter Terrorism</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Gender Identity</p></td><td><p>Simon Wren, Director of Communication, Communication Directorate</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Diversity and Inclusion (Overview)</p></td><td><p>Sir Charles Montgomery, Director General, Border Force</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>As Champions, they see themselves as role models, widely recognised as a supporter and champion of diversity and inclusion with a key role to play in embedding diversity and inclusion into all aspects of the Home Office. The Home Office views this as an opportunity to make a real difference to the experience of our people, ensuring an inclusive Home Office that values the contribution of everyone.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-01-10T18:02:26.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661750/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661750/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661750/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-19","Home Office: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, who the diversity champion is on her departmental board.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","58238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661751","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>Advice and guidance on protective security and preparedness to terrorist threats is provided by specialist Counter-Terrorism Security Advisors (CTSAs) who operate in every police region.</p><p>We do not publically provide a breakdown of this funding or resources by force, region or capability for security reasons. The number of CTSAs in post in each year since 2010 was as follows:</p><p>April 2010 -191 (figure includes Police Scotland and Police Service of Northern Ireland)</p><p>April 2011 – 227 (figure includes Police Scotland and Police Service of Northern Ireland)</p><p>April 2012 – 226 (figure includes Police Scotland and Police Service of Northern Ireland)</p><p>April 2013 – 204 (figure includes Police Scotland and Police Service of Northern Ireland)</p><p>April 2014 – 188 (figures includes Police Scotland and Police Service of Northern Ireland)</p><p>April 2015 - 146 (England and Wales only, this figure includes 4 Counter Terrorism Awareness Advisers, CTAAs, dedicated towards the provision of CT awareness advice).</p><p>April 2016 – 157 (England and Wales only, this figure includes 20 Counter Terrorism Awareness Advisers dedicated towards the provision of CT awareness advice). The Government’s aims to have 171 staff in post by the end of 2016/17 (145 CTSAs and 26 CTAAs). These planned changes to resource are for the effective and efficient delivery of future advice and guidance, whilst ensuring they maintain their fundamental role as part of wider police capabilities to safeguard the security of the public.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2017-01-09T16:28:31.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661751/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661751/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661751/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-19","Police: Counter-terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many counter terrorism security advisers were employed in each police force in England and Wales in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","58117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661752","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>We consider all asylum claims in a sensitive manner on an individual, objective and impartial basis ensuring that all cases are managed effectively throughout the asylum process to avoid unnecessary delay.</p><p>All members of staff who make decisions in asylum receive training on inter-national and domestic law and safeguarding issues supplemented by a mentoring programme with an experienced caseworker that can last up to 6 months. Within the training there are specific sections that detail torture and Medico Legal Reports and how they should be used and analysed in asylum claims.</p><p>Asylum Operations recently received funding from the Asylum Migration and Integration Fund to review and redevelop its training prospectus. As part of that work, Asylum Operations is liaising with a range of external stakeholders - including migrant charities and non-governmental organisations - to ensure a robust and effective safeguarding training product.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-09T18:08:08.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661752/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661752/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661752/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-19","Immigration Officers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans her Department has to introduce a training programme for immigration caseworkers on medical evidence of torture.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","58122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661753","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The number of enforced returns by age is published in table rt_03 (returns data tables) in ‘Immigration Statistics, July - September 2016’, available from the Home Office website at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/572380/returns2-q3-2016-tables.ods</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-09T18:09:53.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661753/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661753/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661753/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-19","Asylum: Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many failed asylum seekers under the age of 18 were deported in December in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","58115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661754","Home Office","false","2017-01-17","<p>Advice and guidance on protective security and preparedness to terrorist threats is provided by specialist Counter-Terrorism Security Advisors (CTSAs) who operate in every police region.</p><p>The Home Office funds CTSAs as part of a wider grant payment to the police in England and Wales for specific counter-terrorism purposes. We do not publically provide a breakdown of this funding or resources by force, region or capability for security reasons.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2017-01-17T14:17:17.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661754/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661754/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661754/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-19","Police: Counter-terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much funding each police force in England and Wales received from her Department to employ counter terrorism security advisers in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","58116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661755","Home Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>Heathrow airport is currently the only provider to publish queue statistics on its website:</p><p>http://www.heathrow.com/company/company-news-and-information/performance/airport-operations/border-force</p><p>There were only five ports which fell below the 95% SLA performance target from 2012. Data before 2012 is not available. Data for December 2016 is not yet available.</p><p>The performance data relates to passenger queuing times – defined as when a passenger / vehicle joins a static body of people / line of vehicles to when they arrive at the UK Border control desk - and as such excludes transaction times for clearance.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-19T13:36:39.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661755/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661755/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661755/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-19","Immigration Controls: Airports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the longest period of time a (a) UK or EEA national and (b) non-EU citizen had to wait during December before passing through border checks at (i) Heathrow, (ii) Gatwick, (iii) Manchester, (iv) Stansted and (v) Luton airports was in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","58118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661756","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>We have worked closely with the French authorities to support the clearance of the Calais camp and to transfer children eligible to come to the UK. Since 10 October, we have transferred over 750 children from France. The current phase has been concluded. More children will be transferred from across Europe under the Immigration Act in the coming months, including from France.</p><p>We will continue to meet our obligation under the Dublin Regulation to transfer unaccompanied refugee children to the UK where a family link has been established.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-09T18:11:09.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661756/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661756/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661756/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-19","Refugees: Calais","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department has suspended all processing and admission of migrants formerly at Calais.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","58113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661758","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>The diversity champion on the Departmental Board is Joy Hutcheon, Director General for Finance and Corporate Performance.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-09T16:58:12.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661758/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661758/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661758/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-19","Department for International Development: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, who the diversity champion is on her departmental board.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","58239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661759","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>The city of Aleppo is now fully under the control of the Assad regime. The UN has gained partial access to most neighbourhoods in eastern Aleppo, formerly under opposition control, to carry out assessments and start responding to needs. The UK supports fully the UN’s call for unhindered access to all areas of Aleppo in order to meet humanitarian needs.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-09T16:49:45.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661759/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661759/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661759/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-19","Syria: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent reports she has received on the availability and accessibility of aid routes into Aleppo.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","58223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661760","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>DFID spent approximately £15.3 million over the last three years on bilateral projects exclusively focused on improving mental health services and on related research.</p><p>DFID funding has, for example, helped Ghana establish a Mental Health Authority and train 3,953 health workers, and generated evidence on how to strengthen mental health care in poor countries. A further £117 million was provided to improve the health of people affected by the conflict in Syria, and a core part of this is psychosocial support and counselling. In addition DFID’s wider work including our support to multilateral health organisations contributes to improving mental health care.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-09T17:02:20.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661760/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661760/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661760/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-19","Developing Countries: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much Official Development Assistance funding was provided to mental health projects in the past three years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","58216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661761","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>The UK has pledged £2.3 billion in response to the Syria crisis, our largest ever response to a single humanitarian crisis. With this funding, we are providing life-saving support to millions of Syrians, including some of the most vulnerable. Through UN and NGO partners, we are delivering food, clean water, shelter, and healthcare. Between February 2012 and August 2016, we provided over 16.4 million monthly food rations, medical support to over 3.7 million people, and relief packages to over 5.5 million people (including essential winter and household items, such as blankets).</p><p>When carrying out humanitarian assessments and responding to humanitarian needs, DFID and our partners take into account the specific needs of those who may be more vulnerable. In Syria and the region, for example, we have funded the vaccination of 500,000 children against childhood diseases, provided 200,000 flu vaccinations for the elderly and other vulnerable groups, and distributed a range of health support targeted at conditions prevalent in the elderly and those with ongoing health needs, including diabetes and high blood pressure.</p><p>Our partners prioritise the identification and protection of unaccompanied children, and provide them with legal advisory services to mitigate the protection risks that they face.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-09T16:48:32.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661761/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661761/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661761/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-19","Syria: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what humanitarian assistance the Government is providing to (a) orphaned children, (b) the elderly, (c) the sick and (d) other vulnerable groups among Syrian civilians.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","58222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661762","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-09","<p>The main construction phase of the St Helena Airport is now complete. There are no plans currently for further construction works. Should that situation change, we would expect the environmental impact of any future works to be fully considered.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-09T17:15:25.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661762/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661762/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661762/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-19","St Helena: Airports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether the Government plans to undertake additional environmental impact assessments ahead of any further construction works required at St Helena airport.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","58276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661763","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-23","<p>Access to justice is not just about proximity to a court and we are committed to providing alternative ways for our users to access our services that are more efficient and convenient for them.</p><p>As we modernise our courts and bring more services online we will replace unfamiliar legal language with more straightforward wording. This will help make our services more accessible for everyone.</p><p>All new online services will be developed to ensure users have access to facilities to assist them throughout the process. This will include; step-by-step online guidance to assist people when completing forms online, telephone support and free of charge, face to face support from an HMCTS representative. This will be available at locations across the country, including rural areas.</p><p>We want a justice system that works for everyone. That means users who are not comfortable using digital channels will be provided with an alternative and given the support they need in choosing an option which works best for them.</p><p>Crucially it will not be compulsory for the public to use digital channels.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-01-23T15:00:32.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661763/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661763/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661763/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-19","Courts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what measures her Department will put in place to provide continued access to court services for people who cannot access those services online after the implementation of the proposals outlined in its Transforming our Justice System consultation paper, published in September 2016.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","58200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661764","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-13","<p>HMCTS staff can already be authorised to exercise judicial powers across many jurisdictions. Often these powers form part of a wider role, and it is not possible to separate the funding required for them to make judicial decisions from the rest of their role.</p><p>An assessment of the potential costs and benefits across the jurisdictions will be published alongside any forthcoming legislation on this matter and will be subject to decisions made by relevant Procedure Rules Committees</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-01-13T15:04:31.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661764/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661764/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661764/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-19","Courts: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to paragraph 1.5 of her Department's paper on Transforming Our Justice System, published in September 2016, what estimate she has made of the funding required to train and remunerate court staff to make judicial decisions.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","58260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661765","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-25","<p>Justin Russell (Director General for Prisons, Offender and Youth Justice Policy) is the Overall Diversity Champion for the Ministry of Justice. Justin took over this role on the 25 October 2016.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-01-25T16:45:49.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661765/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661765/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661765/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-19","Ministry of Justice: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, who the diversity champion is on her departmental board.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","58240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661766","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-13","<p>Information on the number of Full Time Equivalent (FTE) staff employed by HMCTS by jurisdiction in each of the last four years is set out in the table below. Information prior to 2013 is not held centrally.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="3"><p>FTE</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Date</p></td><td><p>Crown</p></td><td><p>County</p></td><td><p>Magistrates’</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31/03/2013</p></td><td><p>2,076</p></td><td><p>4,143</p></td><td><p>5,059</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31/03/2014</p></td><td><p>2,000</p></td><td><p>4,141</p></td><td><p>4,758</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31/03/2015</p></td><td><p>2,050</p></td><td><p>3,761</p></td><td><p>4,352</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31/03/2016</p></td><td><p>2,133</p></td><td><p>3,764</p></td><td><p>4,065</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","58143 ; 58144","2017-01-13T15:00:21.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661766/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661766/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661766/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-19","County Courts: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many full-time equivalent staff have been employed in county courts in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","58145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661767","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-13","<p>The government encourages people to use mediation as a way of resolving disputes.</p><p>In civil cases, there is an expectation that parties consider alternatives to court before issuing their claim and the court may impose costs sanctions if they do not do so. Where proceedings have been issued, HM Courts and Tribunals Service also offer mediation for small claims with a value under £10,000, where both parties consent.</p><p>The government remains committed to promoting family mediation, and legal aid remains available in such cases.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-01-13T15:05:40.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661767/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661767/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661767/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-19","Dispute Resolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what funding her Department provides for dispute resolution within the justice system; what progress her Department has made in its aim to settle more disputes out of court; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","58140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661768","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-23","<p>The Ministry is committed to ensuring the justice system is supported by a suite of high quality language services that meet the needs of all those that require them.</p><p> </p><p>The new language service contracts which began on 31 October 2016 and are subject to robust governance arrangements.</p><p> </p><p>These include monthly meetings with suppliers and stakeholders to monitor and discuss, in detail, the quality of the services being provided and performance against contractual performance indicators. The contracts also provide for the Ministry to audit the suppliers to verify the accuracy of contractual payments, management information, and compliance with contractual obligations.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Ministry has awarded a contract to 'The Language Shop' (part of the London Borough of Newham) to provide independent quality assurance of the services provided under the other contracts, including those awarded to the thebigword Ltd. The Language Shop undertakes this assurance in a number of ways, including managing the Ministry’s register of interpreters, conducting an annual audit of supplier processes for introducing new linguists, and a programme of 'spot checks' of interpreters undertaking assignments.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-01-23T15:10:27.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661768/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661768/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661768/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-19","The Big Word","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how her Department assesses the quality of service provided to it by The Big Word Ltd; and with what frequency such assessments take place.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","58170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661769","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-08","<p>The Department spent approximately £145,000 developing and testing electronic file covers for magistrates’ courts. This figure includes both supplier and staff costs.</p><p> </p><p>These costs were incurred over the period May 2014 to September 2015.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-02-08T15:44:31.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661769/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661769/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661769/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-19","Magistrates' Courts: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much her Department has spent on developing and testing electronic file covers for magistrates' courts.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","58141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661770","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-13","<p>We are investing close to £1 billion to reform and digitise our courts and tribunals, and improve the experience of our users. We are already using technology such as video and telephony to enable more flexible working across all jurisdictions, particularly in crime.</p><p>In future, where appropriate, some proceedings will be dealt with entirely online without the need for a hearing. Where a hearing is still required, some hearings will be moved out of the traditional courtroom and conducted by video-conference or telephone.</p><p>There will always be a place for the solemnity of the physical court room for the most serious and complex cases, and will make greater use of technology to support these hearings in future.</p><p>The most appropriate mode of hearing will be subject to judicial discretion, and so we are unable to provide estimated volumes for virtual hearings in future.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-01-13T15:02:50.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661770/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661770/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661770/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-19","Courts: Video Conferencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate she has made of the proportion of cases that will take place in virtual hearings in each jurisdiction in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","58142"
