"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661816","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-10","<p>The information requested is not available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","58277","2017-01-10T14:09:15.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661816/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661816/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661816/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-19","Means-tested Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the total value is of (a) amounts recovered from claimants as recoverable hardship payments and (b) recoverable hardship payments written off due to the recipient being in 26 weeks of continuous qualifying employment in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","58278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661817","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-12","<p>Between April 2011 and March 2016 DWP awarded no contracts to iNHouse Communications Ltd.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-12T13:03:19.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661817/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661817/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661817/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-19","Department for Work and Pensions: iNHouse Communications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department has awarded any commercial contracts to iNHouse Communications Ltd in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","58309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661818","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-10","<p>There have been no communications with this company with regard to any tender process.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-10T16:12:28.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661818/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661818/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661818/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-19","Department for Work and Pensions: iNHouse Communications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department is in communication with iNHouse Communications Ltd in relation to any ongoing commercial tender process.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","58308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661819","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-09","<p>There are no current plans to review the ’10 year rule’ with respect to the prescription for osteoarthritis of the knee for specific mining occupations.</p><p>I am advised on matters relating to the Industrial Injuries Scheme by the Industrial Injuries Advisory Council (IIAC). IIAC keeps all occupational diseases under continuous review, including osteoarthritis of the knee, and is always ready to receive and consider robust scientific evidence from any source.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-09T15:48:13.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661819/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661819/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661819/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-19","Industrial Injuries Disablement Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans he has to review the 10-year rule with respect to the prescription for osteoarthritis of the knee in former miners; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","58344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661820","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-09","<p>The information requested is not available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-09T12:24:02.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661820/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661820/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661820/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-19","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of how many (a) parents and (b) lone parents with a youngest child aged three (i) nationally, (ii) by region, (iii) by local authority and (iv) by parliamentary constituency will be expected to look for work if they want to claim universal credit or tax credits from April 2017.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","58104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661821","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-10","<p>This information requested is not available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-10T12:55:05.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661821/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661821/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661821/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-19","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of how many people in the disabled working-age population in the Glasgow South constituency are using services at (a) Castlemilk and (b) Langside jobcentres.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","58153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661822","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-10","<p>After 20 years, the PFI contract covering the majority of the department’s buildings expires on 31 March 2018. This gives the department a once in a generation opportunity to review what offices it needs.</p><p> </p><p>The department has around 900 offices. It needs to make better use of the space it occupies and reduce the amount of empty space that it has, reducing overall estate costs.</p><p> </p><p>The department is committed to retaining an accessible jobcentre network and continuing to serve customers in all areas of the country. Increasingly, our customers access many of our services on-line. We tailor our service so that face-to-face contact can be focused on those who need extra support from us.</p><p> </p><p>This exercise is not about reducing headcount, it is about the buildings the department works in.</p><p> </p><p>Approximately 260 DWP members of staff are expected to be relocated as a result of proposed jobcentre closures in Glasgow.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-10T13:12:58.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661822/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661822/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661822/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-19","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many of his Department's staff are expected to be relocated as a result of proposed jobcentre closures in Glasgow.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","58154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661823","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government has set out its plans for the sale of the Green Investment Bank in the document “Green Investment Bank: sale of shares” (Cm 9214). As stated in this report, the Government is fully reflecting the National Audit Office’s recommendations on how Government should approach such assets sales, which includes preparing a full business case and undertaking a robust valuation process.</p><p> </p><p>The Government response to the Environmental Audit Committee report ‘The Future of the Green Investment Bank’ (Cm 9201) set out alternative options considered for the sale of the Green Investment Bank.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has committed to lay a report before Parliament on the sale of the Green Investment Bank, as soon as reasonably practicable after a disposal of shares has taken place, and this is also a requirement in the Enterprise Act 2016.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-01-09T14:26:33.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661823/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661823/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661823/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-19","Green Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if the Government will publish a comparative assessment of the effect on the public purse of (a) a full sale, (b) retaining full or partial government ownership and (c) other ownership options of the Green Investment Bank.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","58215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661824","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has two diversity and inclusion champions on the departmental board - Angie Ridgwell (Director General, Finance and Corporate Services) and Gareth Davies (Director General, Business and Science).</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-09T15:06:25.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661824/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661824/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661824/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-19","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, who the diversity champion is on his departmental board.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","58229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661825","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-09","<p>EDF has a strong incentive to build Hinkley Point C on time (i.e. by 2025) because of the loss of expected revenues after that time if not.</p><p> </p><p>If EDF does not start generating four years after 2025, then there will be reductions to the contract term; this means that for every day that HPC is late, the period of time where EDF gets increased certainty on the price of its electricity will be reduced.</p><p> </p><p>If HPC is not generating electricity by 2033, there is an option in the contract to cancel the contract. Finally, EDF will pay any extra costs if the cost of building the plant goes over budget.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-09T10:52:38.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661825/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661825/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661825/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-19","Hinkley Point C Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what sanctions are available to his Department should construction of Hinkley Point C run behind schedule or over budget.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","58102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661826","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-09","<p>Since 2000 there has been one proposal put forward for a development consent order for a new nuclear power station at Hinkley Point C.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-09T10:53:49.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661826/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661826/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661826/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-19","Nuclear Power Stations: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many proposals have been submitted for the construction of new nuclear power stations since 2000.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","58101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661827","Department for Education","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government expects to lay Regulations implementing changes to student support for undergraduates in 2017/18 early in the New Year. The Regulations will be subject to the negative resolution procedure which is set out in statute.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-01-09T10:06:20.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661827/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661827/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661827/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-19","Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 13 December 2016 to Question 56452, when she plans to lay a statutory instrument providing that standard student support regulations enable healthcare students to apply for loans; and whether that statutory instruments affirmative will be made by the negative or resolution procedure.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","58205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661828","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-09","<p>As part of the sale process, the Government has asked potential investors to confirm their commitment to the Green Investment Bank’s (GIB) green values and investment principles and how they propose to protect them. Government does not intend to undertake an environmental impact assessment on any potential bidders for GIB.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has committed to lay a report before Parliament on the sale of the Green Investment Bank, as soon as reasonably practicable after a disposal of shares has taken place, and this is also a requirement in the Enterprise Act 2016.</p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-01-09T14:32:07.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661828/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661828/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661828/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-19","Green Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will undertake an environmental impact assessment of current and previous activities of the Government's preferred bidder for the UK Green Investment Bank; and if he will publish any such assessment before the sale of the Government's shares is agreed.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","58119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661829","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-10","<p>We are currently aware of two UK companies operating in Eritrea. The Government of Eritrea places restrictions on the number and type of international businesses that are allowed to operate in the country.</p><p> </p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-01-10T15:32:35.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661829/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661829/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661829/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-19","Overseas Companies: Eritrea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what recent estimate his Department has made of the number of UK-based companies operating in Eritrea.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","58207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661830","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-09","<p>The investment reserve for the Mineworkers’ Pension Scheme totalled £1,066m at the last valuation (dated 30 September 2014). For the British Coal Staff Superannuation Scheme, the investment fund stood at £1,701m when last valued on 31 March 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-09T10:54:59.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661830/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661830/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661830/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-19","Mining: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much is held in the investment reserve funds for the (a) Mineworkers' Pension Scheme and (b) British Coal Staff Superannuation Scheme.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","58096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661831","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-09","<p>The presence of the guarantee has enabled the scheme trustees to invest so as to target surpluses; this has resulted in a 30% increase in payments to members. For this reason, we believe the existing arrangements work well and are fair to all parties.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-09T10:50:49.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661831/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661831/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661831/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-19","Mineworkers' Pension Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will assess the balance of the Mineworkers' Pension Scheme surplus-sharing arrangements.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","58345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661832","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-09","<p>HM Treasury publishes a country and regional breakdown of spend across Government.</p><p>The latest publication can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/country-and-regional-analysis-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/country-and-regional-analysis-2016</a>.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-09T12:58:26.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661832/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661832/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661832/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-19","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the value of (a) staffing expenditure, (b) other revenue costs and (c) capital expenditure by his Department and its arms-length bodies in whole or in part in Yorkshire and the Humber in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","58315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661833","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-13","<p>If a generator is curtailed by the National Electricity Transmission System Operator (NETSO – currently National Grid in England) compensation is provided to that generator under current market arrangements. The Hinkley Point C Contract for Difference provides protection if these market arrangements were to change and the generator is left worse off as a result of such curtailment.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-13T11:04:55.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661833/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661833/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661833/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-19","Hinkley Point C Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether a price has been agreed with the operators of Hinkley Point C to cover periods of low demand and oversupply in which the power station may have to stop generating.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","58272"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661834","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-09","<p>We will be publishing a discussion paper shortly which will form part of an ongoing open and collaborative dialogue to develop the new Industrial Strategy.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-01-09T10:55:52.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661834/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661834/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661834/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-19","Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he expects to publish the consultation on the Government's industrial strategy.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","58321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661835","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Pubs Code Adjudicator has no financial interests in large pub-owning businesses. The Adjudicator updated the register of interests with further details of his shareholding and loans with Fleurets Holdings Ltd on 20 December. The register of interests is available on the Pubs Code Adjudicator website.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-09T12:57:37.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661835/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661835/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661835/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-19","Pubs Code Adjudicator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will make it his policy to ensure that the Pubs Code Adjudicator notifies pub tenants of (a) his financial interests in large pub-owning businesses, (b) the size and value of his existing shareholding in Fleurets and (c) the value of loans owned to him by Fleurets.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","58342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661836","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Competition and Markets Authority is an independent enforcement body and draws on a range of sources when carrying out such investigations. The Department does not hold this information.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-09T12:57:02.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661836/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661836/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661836/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-19","Tickets: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if his Department will publish the evidence collected by the Competition and Markets Authority supporting its compliance review into consumer protection law in the online secondary tickets market which was published on 19 December 2016.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","58297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661837","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-10","<p>The Smart Meter Roll-out Cost Benefit Analysis (CBA) published on 10 November estimates the costs and benefits for suppliers, consumers’ savings and energy networks – the document is available at:</p><p>www.gov.uk/government/publications/smart-meter-roll-out-gb-cost-benefit-analysis.</p><p>The smart meter rollout is expected to deliver significant net benefits to Great Britain, estimated overall at £5.7 billion over the lifetime of the programme.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-10T11:37:15.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661837/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661837/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661837/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-19","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether his Department has made an estimate of the potential net benefit of smart meter roll-out in (a) cost savings for suppliers, (b) cost savings for consumers and (c) the transmission system; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for John Penrose","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","58256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661838","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-13","<p>It is the responsibility of developers to consult with local communities at the pre-application stage of proposals for nationally significant energy infrastructure which require development consent under the Planning Act 2008.</p><p> </p><p>Applications for such projects are examined by the Planning Inspectorate which reports with its recommendation to my Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, who will then decide whether or not to grant development consent.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State will take into account the community consultations carried out by the developer in reaching his decisions on whether or not to grant development consent but it would not be appropriate for the Department to comment on those consultations at the pre-application stage in the process.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-13T11:03:41.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661838/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661838/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661838/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-19","Nuclear Power Stations: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the local community response to the pre-planning consultations for Bradwell B and Sizewell C Power Stations.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","58262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661839","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-13","<p>It is up to the developer to decide on what highway infrastructure improvements to facilitate construction traffic to the site it wishes to include in its application after giving proper consideration to the responses it receives to its pre-application consultation. The developer is currently consulting on a number of proposals linked to Sizewell C – with the consultation period running from 23rd November 2016 through to 3rd February 2017. Funding of highway infrastructure to be included in an application for development consent for Sizewell C would be a matter for the developer to consider.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-13T11:02:06.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661839/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661839/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661839/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-19","Sizewell C Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what information his Department holds on plans to improve highway infrastructure around the construction sites of Sizewell C to facilitate additional construction traffic; and who will be responsible for funding such improvements.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","58263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661840","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Industrial Strategy is a critical part of the Government’s ambition to build an economy that works for everyone. Government funding for business support across England is awarded to local areas via Growth Deals agreed with Local Enterprise Partnerships.</p><p>The Growth Deal agreed with the North East’s Local Enterprise Partnership will see nearly £330m invested in the North East economy between 2016 and 2021. This investment in innovation, skills, business support, transport, and economic assets will drive economic growth in the North East. Over the lifetime of the Deal the Local Enterprise Partnership estimates that up to 5,000 new jobs could be created and up to £130m additional public and private investment.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-01-09T15:04:50.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661840/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661840/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661840/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-19","Industry: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much funding to which industries in the North East the Government plans to provide (a) over the next three years; and if he will estimate how many jobs will be created by that finding.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","58251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661841","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government recognises the importance of ensuring regions and organisations have stability and certainty in the period leading up to our departure from the European Union. My right hon. Friend the Chancellor of the Exchequer announced in October that funding for European Structural and Investment Fund projects signed before or after the Autumn Statement, and which continue after we have left the EU, will be honoured by the Treasury if they provide strong value for money and are in line with domestic strategic priorities.</p><p>Leaving the EU means we will be able to take our own decisions about how we deliver the policy objectives previously targeted by EU funding. Over the coming months we will consult closely with stakeholders to review all EU funding schemes, thereby ensuring that all funding commitments serve the UK’s national interest.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-09T15:00:14.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661841/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661841/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661841/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-19","Industry: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how he plans to support industries located in the North East that receive funding in the event of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","58252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661842","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-12","<p>Statistics published by the Health and Safety Executive (HSE) in November 2016 show that, in 2014/15 and 2015/16, prosecutions in Great Britain instituted by HSE for health and safety offences (or referred to the Crown Office and Procurator Fiscal Service in Scotland) led to fines totalling £56.3 million. The figures include fines imposed on individuals and all types of organisation. The table below provides a breakdown by year and industrial sector. The data does not include fines resulting from health and safety prosecutions taken by other enforcing organisations such as the Crown Prosecution Service, Office of Road and Rail, or the Office for Nuclear Regulation.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Total fines for prosecution cases instituted by HSE<sup>1</sup> in Great Britain<sup>2</sup>, by industrial sector 2014/15<sup>3</sup> &amp; 2015/16p</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Industrial sector<sup>4</sup></strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong> <strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong> <strong>2015/16p</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>All Industries</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£18,072,811</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£38,266,663</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Agriculture</p></td><td><p>£823,944</p></td><td><p>£612,720</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Mining and Quarrying</p></td><td><p>£473,015</p></td><td><p>£4,164,120</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Manufacturing</p></td><td><p>£4,673,116</p></td><td><p>£12,105,301</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Utility Supply</p></td><td><p>£51,135</p></td><td><p>£4,512,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Water Supply/Waste Management</p></td><td><p>£2,056,270</p></td><td><p>£1,840,445</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Construction</p></td><td><p>£4,258,992</p></td><td><p>£7,805,975</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Distribution, Hotels and Restaurants</p></td><td><p>£367,611</p></td><td><p>£603,202</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Transportation and Storage</p></td><td><p>£1,062,698</p></td><td><p>£3,335,515</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Communications, Business Services and Finance</p></td><td><p>£1,702,070</p></td><td><p>£1,228,875</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Public Administration</p></td><td><p>£312,120</p></td><td><p>£350,515</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Education</p></td><td><p>£160,125</p></td><td><p>£304,115</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Human Health and Social Work activities</p></td><td><p>£1,167,000</p></td><td><p>£967,120</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Arts, Entertainment and Recreation; Other Service activities</p></td><td><p>£964,715</p></td><td><p>£436,760</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Notes</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong><sup>1</sup></strong> HSE does not hold published statistics for the same period that show the level of fines arising from prosecutions instituted by local authorities.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong><sup>2 </sup></strong>In Scotland, HSE investigate potential offences but cannot institute legal proceedings. HSE send a report to the Crown Office and Procurator Fiscal Service (COPFS). COPFS makes the final decision whether to institute legal proceedings and which offences are taken.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong><sup>3 </sup></strong>Year of prosecution is based on when a result has been secured i.e. the prosecution has been completed. The year is from the beginning of April to the end of March.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong><sup>4 </sup></strong>Industrial sector is defined by Section level of the UK Standard Industrial Classification 2007 (SIC2007).</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>p= provisional</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-12T16:15:25.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661842/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661842/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/661842/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-19","Industrial Health and Safety: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the total amount levied in health and safety fines on businesses since 2014; and what amount has been levied in each business sector.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","58199"
